<TEXT>
leo lemay thinks he knows what ben franklin 
would do if he returned to his adopted city and saw the hoopla 
surrounding the 200th anniversary of his death 
first of all hed have a good time said the university of 
delaware professor of english and an organizer of a scholarly 
conference thats one of several events this week marking april 17 
1790 
it was on that date that the 84yearold franklin weakened by 
gout and kidney stones died succumbing to a fever and an abscess 
in his left lung 
he knew it was coming as early as 1786 he wrote having seen 
during a long life a good deal of this world i feel a growing 
curiosity to be acquainted with some other 
the outpouring of grief at the april 21 funeral included a 
halfmilelong procession watched by throngs that filled streets 
and rooftops 
come saturday a more joyful parade will celebrate his full life 
we dont want anyone standing on the curb watching this parade 
we want everyone in it said hobart cawood superintendent of 
independence national historical park 
among the invited participants are those whose lives or 
professions were touched by franklins legacy and since he was a 
printer publisher journalist builder folk philosopher patriot 
inventor scientist diplomat and politician thats a lot of 
lives touched 
weve got many other groups that are associated with 
franklin cawood said such as the first insurance company 
which he founded pennsylvania hospital which he founded the us 
postal service since he was the first postmaster general the fire 
department which he started all of these have units in the 
procession 
of course all americans have been touched by the declaration of 
independence and the constitution in which franklin had a hand 
ask someone who do you associate with philadelphia more 
than anyone else even though hes been dead 200 years people will 
say ben franklin throughout the world cawood said 
were not celebrating his funeral but after he died he left 
something very important behind he left institutions and 
organizations and a reputation and so many things that continue 
right up to this year 
franklin also bequeathed 1000 pounds sterling to pennsylvania 
and philadelphia in trust to provide lowinterest loans to young 
married artificers meaning apprentices starting their own 
businesses 
he made a similar bequest to massachusetts and boston the 
hometown he left as a 17yearold runaway 
franklin directed that the fund be dissolved 200 years after his 
death and split between city and state now comes the question of 
what to do with the money which today is worth about 45 million 
in massachusetts and 2 million in pennsylvania 
philadelphias share 520000 will be used to help students in 
the trades crafts and applied sciences a special commission 
announced tuesday 
franklin said laborers and handicraftsmen are the wealth and 
support of the nation and we are hoping that by these grants we 
may increase the number of competent handicraftsmen in 
philadelphia said whitfield bell commission chairman 
as for pennsylvanias share the state senate has passed a bill 
that would give the states 15 million to the franklin institute 
a philadelphia museum devoted to science and franklin in 
pennsylvania until now the franklin fund has been used to make 
mortgage loans at below market rates to low and moderateincome 
workers 
to lemay who has written several books on franklin he is one 
of the very greatest geniuses of the 18th century 
you can be interested in him as a great scientist probably 
the second greatest in the 18th century after newton and you can 
be interested in him as certainly the greatest writer of colonial 
america lemay said 
lemay helped bring together historians and professors from 
around the country as well as from france england and germany 
to discuss the great man at a conference reappraising benjamin 
franklin a bicentennial perspective 
among the topics eat not to dulness drink not to elevation 
franklins journalistic writings on drunkards and drinking 
franklin as crime reporter and benjamin franklin as founding 
father of american humor 
and of course the ageold debate was franklin too french 
</TEXT>
