<TEXT>
a government index that measures drought 
severity over the long haul shows that much of the midwest and 
great plains has recovered from the moisture deficits of the late 
1980s 
the socalled palmer index used by the national weather service 
shows huge areas of moist conditions east of the rocky mountains 
and relatively small areas of severe and extreme drought remaining 
in north dakota and adjacent parts of south dakota minnesota iowa 
and nebraska and the southern part of florida 
most of the west however is still gripped by severe and 
extreme longterm drought 
according to the agency the index depicts prolonged abnormal 
dryness or wetness over periods of months and years the index 
changes little from week to week and reflects the longterm runoff 
recharge and deep percolation of moisture into the subsoil 
the index was used in a weekly report by the governments joint 
agricultural weather facility operated by the agriculture and 
commerce departments 
weather analysts said the overall indications from the index and 
state reports are that moisture supplies are abundant in the 
central and eastern corn belt adequate to short in the western 
corn belt and mostly short in the spring wheat region 
in ohio and indiana for example topsoil moisture was reported 
to be 48 percent and 65 percent in surplus respectively the cold 
wet soils have limited fieldwork in indiana and caused 
unhealthylooking stands of wheat and oats in ohio 
conditions improve to the west with about onefifth of 
illinois topsoils rated either short or surplus and 28 percent of 
iowa rated short and 72 percent adequate the report said this 
contrasts favorably with the situation 12 months ago when topsoils 
rated 81 percent short in iowa and 44 percent short in illinois 
but the report said subsoil moisture remains surprisingly low 
in the western corn belt with iowa reporting 76 percent short and 
nebraska 88 percent short 
th report showed that it would take up to seven inches of 
additional precipitation to restore subsoil moisture reserves 
although most parched areas of the northern plains would need less 
than that 
for north dakota the nations most important spring wheat 
state all indicators show that drought remains a concern the 
report said a dry march following the driest winter on record 
did nothing to remove the lingering effects of the 1988 drought 
although north dakota is most affected right now surrounding 
states also are of concern and the area clearly bears close 
watching in coming weeks the report said 
