<TEXT>
a supreme court ruling allowing judges 
to order schools to raise taxes for desegregation wouldnt have 
come about if lawmakers and the public had met their 
responsibility says the head of kansas citys schools 
the high court ruled 90 wednesday that judges cannot directly 
impose a tax increase as us district judge russell clark did in 
the kansas city case in 1987 but in a 54 vote it upheld a federal 
appeals court decision that clark could instead order the school 
board to raise taxes 
julia hill newly elected school board president said the issue 
wouldnt have even been before the court if voters hadnt turned 
down school tax increases time and again 
i would have loved for the previous tax levies to pass when 
they were presented to the public sometimes three times she 
said at a news conference 
when democracy fails sometimes people have to pay and 
democracy failed here in kansas city and it also failed at the 
state level 
all of this could have been alleviated by changing some 
boundary lines 20 years ago but nobody did anything so were at a 
state now where were under a federal court order 
before 1954 missouri law required schools to be racially 
segregated in the following 35 years the percentage of black 
students in kansas citys school district rose from 225 percent to 
about 75 percent 
black parents sued in 1977 over the decline of what had become 
predominantly black schools alleging black students were being 
denied equal educational opportunities 
clark ruled in 1987 that the schools have literally rotted 
and ordered state and district officials to upgrade them he 
ordered the state to pay threefourths of the remedial costs and 
the school district the rest 
district voters had rejected six proposals since 1970 to raise 
taxes for education 
clark had nearly doubled the local property tax from 205 to 4 
per 100 of assessed valuation to help finance the improvements 
the increase raised about 30 million 
civil rights forces praised the supreme court decision 
its a powerful reaffirmation that state laws may not impede 
the vindication of constitutional rights the rights of school 
children said paul holtzman of the washingtonbased lawyers 
committee for civil rights under law 
