<DOCNO> AP900419-0033 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
women who sought to have baby girls have been 
impregnated with female embryos selected from a test tube 
scientists reported today 
the results obtained by way of a new embryoscreening procedure 
designed to prevent genetic diseases are the first reported 
pregnancies using embryos tested to reveal gender researchers said 
in the british journal nature 
two of three pregnant women expect twins this summer study 
coauthor alan handyside said in a telephone interview the third 
expects one child he said 
the laboratory test identified the sex of the microscopic 
embryos only three days after fertilization he said 
the women were at risk of transmitting serious genetic diseases 
to a male child handyside said the test also could be used 
without a medical justification to select the sex of a child but 
handyside said he would consider that unethical 
further research might provide a way to screen out embryos that 
would develop serious genetic diseases thereby removing the 
prospect of abortions in those cases researchers said 
the work was reported by handyside and colleagues at the royal 
postgraduate medical school at hammsmith hospital in london 
lab techniques have been used before to determine a babys sex 
in 1986 a new orleans fertility institute announced the birth of a 
boy whose sex had been selected during in vitro fertilization 
which is done in the laboratory that case involved selecting sperm 
to produce a boy 
but sperm selection has not proved reliable said dr maria 
bustillo of the genetics and ivf institute in fairfax va and it 
does not hold the promise of diagnosing genetic diseases before an 
embryo is implanted as embryo analysis does she said wednesday 
it is not clear how many couples would choose the embryo 
analysis which requires in vitro fertilization rather than 
conceiving naturally and then considering an abortion after 
undergoing a standard genetic analysis of the fetus she said 
but it may be possible someday to allow a woman to conceive 
naturally and then flush out the embryo for analysis she said 
then reimplant it if desired 
some 200 genetic diseases that typically affect only boys have 
been identified including the most severe form of muscular 
dystrophy hemophilia and a form of mental retardation handyside 
said 
the embryo analysis involves collecting eggs from a woman 
fertilizing them in a test tube and letting them grow to eightcell 
embryos a single cell is removed from each embryo to see if it 
contains a bit of genetic material that indicates the presence of a 
y chromosome which would mean the embryo is destined to become a 
boy 
the three pregnant women were each given two embryos to increase 
the chance of pregnancy handyside said 
for families that risk passing on serious genetic disease to 
males the embryo procedure should be less emotionally trying than 
an abortion said pediatrician and ethicist dr kathleen nolan at 
the hastings center in briarcliff manor ny 
she and ethicist arthur caplan at the university of minnesota 
said the technique is probably too cumbersome and costly to make it 
widely popular for choosing a babys sex without any medical reason 
but they said thorny issues could arise if researchers find an 
easier way to analyze genetic traits of an embryo and learn to 
predict a variety of diseases and personal traits 
many people would oppose using embryo analysis to pick a childs 
hair color or sex for no medical reason just as many would support 
use of the technique if the embryo were certain to develop a 
serious disease nolan said 
but between those two extremes lies a huge gray zone in 
terms of how to decide an embryo isnt good enough for 
implantation she said 
some might consider it socially very undesirable for a woman 
to take a 50 percent chance of having a child who is going to be 
obese since those children are likely to get into more medical 
problems and cost the society she said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

