heres a look at what is at stake economically for 
lithuania and the soviet union if the baltic republic is isolated 
 
in the soviet economic arsenal 
lithuania receives all of its oil gas and diesel fuel from 
the soviet union paying subsidized prices at world market prices 
lithuania would run a deficit of 700 million for oil alone 
it also receives all of its metals cotton tractors and 
automobiles from the soviet union 
it receives 58 percent of its sugar from cuba via the soviet 
union 
it receives 37 percent of its concentrated fertilizer from the 
soviet union cotton 100 percent 
it received 400000 tons of grain from the soviets in 1989 
it has only four to five days supply of newsprint and the 
soviets could cut off the supply thus shutting down its newspapers 
 
in lithuanias economic arsenal 
the republic sends to the soviet union 15 percent of the 
nations total production including household electrical meters 
100 percent television set components 70 percent and tractor 
components 30 percent 
it produces much more meat 530000 metric tons in 1987 eggs 
12 million metric tons in 1987 milk 31 million metric tons in 
1987 and other dairy products than it consumes so it could cut 
off the rest of the soviet union from its surplus 
textile products are shipped to factories in the soviet union 
including one plant in leningrad that employs 18000 workers 
the shutdown of the pipeline to the mazeikiai refinery also 
means a curtailment of supplies to the republics of estonia latvia 
and byelorussia a shutdown of a natural gas pipeline would 
interrupt the flow of gas to kaliningrad part of the russian 
republic west of lithuania 
lithuania could demand world prices for exporting soviet 
products through its baltic ports including klaipeda 
