per capita personal income growth slowed in 
new england for the second straight year in l989 and failed to 
match the national average in the plains southwest and far west 
states the government said today 
new england had a second consecutive year of decelerating per 
capita income growth in 1989 the commerce department said in its 
semiannual report per capita income in new england grew 66 
percent in 1989 down from 83 percent in 1988 and 86 percent in 
1987 
despite the slowdown new englands per capita income of 21509 
topped all other regions of the country according to the survey by 
the departments bureau of economic analysis 
by contrast per capita incomes grew 55 percent to 16231 in 
the plains 56 percent to 19153 in the far west and 61 percent 
to 15231 in the southwest the department said 
it reported the national growth rate was 65 percent and the 
average per capita personal income was 17567 
the mideast posted the highest growth rate up 71 percent it 
was followed by the great lakes region up 70 percent and the 
southeast and rocky mountain states both up 67 percent 
it was the third consecutive year of accelerating growth in the 
rocky mountains but despite the pickup it still was 13 percent 
below the us average of 17567 
per capita personal income is the annual total personal income 
of residents divided by the resident population 
states with the highest incomes were connecticut with an 
average 24604 new jersey 23764 massachusetts 22196 
alaska 21173 and maryland 21020 
at the lowest end were mississippi with an average 11835 west 
virginia 12529 arkansas 12984 utah 13027 and louisiana 
13041 
new england posted wellaboveaverage growth earlier in the 
1980s the department said the deceleration last year was caused 
by the smallest earnings increases in manufacturing and private 
servicetype industries since 1975 and the first construction 
earnings decline since 1975 
