nepali congress leader ganesh man singh who declined birendras 
proposal to become prime minister because of poor health said 
economic reforms were important but cannot be achieved in a day 
and people should not have unwarranted aspirations 
the swearingin capped the prodemocracy movement that started 
feb 18 with a series of marches and strikes that spawned a popular 
groundswell in this remote himalayan monarchy where political 
activity had been forbidden since 1961 
on april 6 police opened fire on 200000 demonstrators marching 
on birendras palace killing 200 according to witnesses the 
government claims no more than 10 died 
two days later the king yielded to the mass movement led by the 
nepali congress and the united left front and lifted a 29year ban 
on political parties 
on april 16 birendra dissolved the partyless legislature and 
announced the resignation of his governments prime minister 
lokendra bahadur chand 
those had been the main conditions of the nepali congress and 
the united left front for joining a palaceproposed interim 
government 
the ministers oath called for allegiance to nepals present 
constitution which gives nearabsolute powers to the king 
but bhattarai has said a proposed constitutional reforms 
commission would draft a new constitution reducing the kings 
powers and possibly make nepal a constitutional monarchy 
the new government has also promised to hold multiparty 
elections within a year 
the nepali congress formed the countrys first democratically 
elected government in 1959 but it lasted only 20 months before 
birendras father king mahendra dismissed it accusing it of 
corruption and poor administration 
bhattarai was parliament speaker in the 195960 government he 
was jailed for nine years immediately after mahendra dissolved that 
government and spent five more years in jail at different times for 
political agitation 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

