<TEXT>
attorney general dick thornburgh today 
confirmed that his chief spokesman had declined to steer a cbs 
reporter off a story about a criminal investigation involving rep 
william h gray iii dpa 
thornburgh who ordered an intensive criminal investigation of 
unauthorized disclosures about the case said in a statement that 
press secretary david runkel was following his standing 
instructions by declining to wave cbs reporter rita braver off the 
story 
thornburgh said runkel did not violate any department rules 
because he had not intended to confirm the story by refusing to 
deny information ms braver had obtained from other sources 
several days after cbs reported that gray was a subject of the 
probe the justice department issued a statement that the 
congressman was not a target of the investigation 
the department said at the time that gray was cooperating with 
the investigation of alleged financial irregularities in his 
congressional office 
thornburgh said that runkel in refusing to deny that a probe of 
gray was underway was following my standing instruction that no 
one in the department mislead the media 
unfortunately there are circumstances where a statement of 
the kind likely made here by mr runkel may be used by a reporter 
as confirmation of a story the attorney general said 
the attorney general who was attending a hemispheric drug 
enforcement conference in mexico issued the statement in response 
to a story in todays editions of the new york times that runkel 
had played a role in confirming the story reported by ms braver 
last spring 
justice department spokesman daniel eramian who read the 
attorney generals statement to reporters refused to comment on 
the times account that runkel had failed a lie detector test 
during the leak investigation conducted by federal prosecutors and 
the fbi 
thornburgh said that a refusal to deny or wave a reporter off 
a story with which he is confronted by the reporter does not in my 
view constitute misconduct 
a real distinction must be made i believe between an 
unsolicited and affirmative unauthorized disclosure and such a 
confirmation by one responsible for dealing with the media 
the cbs story produced a storm of indignation from democrats on 
capitol hill because it broke as gray was seeking election as house 
majority whip 
democrats charged the leaks from the justice department were 
politically inspired 
thornburgh ordered the justice department to conduct a criminal 
investigation in which more than 100 people were questioned and 
asked to make sworn statements 
runkel has refused to say if he was among those who took lie 
detector tests but has confirmed that he had given testimony before 
a federal grand jury that investigated the matter 
in december thornburgh reported to congress that the 
investigation has not produced sufficient evidence to enable me 
to ascertain that any present employee of the department of justice 
was responsible for the disclosure 
the attorney general responding to pressure from democratic 
lawmakers agreed recently to turn over the report of the 
investigation to the justice departments office of professional 
responsibility 
that unit conducts investigations of misconduct by justice 
department employees and can recommend to the attorney general that 
disciplinary action be taken against individuals 
eramian said the opr review has been completed and the 
attorney general has received that offices advice he declined 
to say what opr had advised 
