<TEXT>
rembrandts night watch 
masterpiece will go back on display may 1 less than one month 
after being sprayed with sulfuric acid by a man believed to be 
mentally disturbed officials said thursday 
no extra security will be introduced to protect the painting 
despite the fact the april 6 attack was the third against the 
rembrandt this century said det de beus spokeswoman for the 
rijksmuseum 
the huge 1642 painting will be returned to its customary 
centerstage spot in the main gallery in the rijksmuseum the 
nations largest treasure trove of art 
a protective veneer layer prevented any damage to the work of 
art according to ms de beus 
the painting can withstand an attack as it is she told the 
associated press adding its not as if it is attacked every 
day the last one was 15 years ago 
in 1975 a dutch schoolmaster claiming to be on a divine mission 
slashed the painting with a knife he was sent to a psychiatric 
hospital where he committed suicide 
during world war i a jobless shoemaker slashed the canvas to 
protest his inability to find work 
in the latest attack a 31yearold dutchman squirted sulfuric 
acid onto the canvas he is undergoing psychiatric treatment 
the acid ate away at the veneer layer leaving several dozen 
white streaks over a onesquareyard area of the canvas the 
painting measures 12by145 feet 
but the paint layer was not harmed at all said ms de beus 
adding that restorers were able to begin refinishing the painting 
last week without having to retouch the paintwork 
working in a dustfree room in the museum the restorers will 
apply the second and final veneer coat friday it is expected to 
dry by may 1 
the protective veneer layer was put on the painting during the 
lengthy restoration that followed the 1975 attack 
night watch a group portrait of 17thcentury dutch 
militiamen draws far more museum viewers than any other painting 
in the netherlands 
the priceless painting renowned for rembrandts mastery of 
light and dark is not insured in line with dutch government policy 
two guards are stationed by the night watch during museum 
hours one of them sprayed a neutralizing agent over the painting 
after the acid attack 
a kneehigh steel barrier keeps viewers approximately two yards 
away from the painting 
