<TEXT>
the senate agriculture committee voted 
thursday to increase spending for research on organic farming 
nearly tenfold 
conventional farming methods promoted by the federal government 
over the last several decades have involved a growing use of 
chemical fertilizers pesticides and herbicides which 
environmentalists and many farmers are beginning to consider 
detrimental 
the committee voted to increase the 45 million being spent 
this year on organic farming to 40 million annually it also 
authorized 10 million a year to train thousands of extension 
agents in nonchemical farming methods 
the authorization is the first major step the government has 
taken to get farming out of the chemical business 
the legislation approved on voice vote also would establish a 
groundwater office in the agriculture department to determine the 
extent of damage to drinking water caused by agriculture chemicals 
and how to correct it 
the proposals were among the provisions of the committees 
agricultural research section or title of its 1990 farm bill 
another provision requires usda to study the effects of climate 
change on food crops and forests 
many scientists believe that a four degree rise in average 
temperature could halve the worlds production of rice the staff 
of life for 70 percent of the worlds population said sen 
patrick leahy dvt chairman of the committee 
federal agriculture officials would be required to integrate 
global warming concerns into plant and forestry research planning 
and decisionmaking and to establish an office of climate change if 
the legislation is adopted 
both the senate and house agriculture committees have been 
working since january on the 1990 farm bill which will set policy 
for virtually all federal agriculture programs during the next five 
years 
the panels are in different stages of completion on the various 
parts of the legislation which they hope to have before the full 
congress by summer 
the senates section on research would authorize an 
unprecedented 400 million over the life of the bill for research 
grants to companies institutions and individuals studying plants 
animals nutrition and health natural resources and the 
environment new products and marketing and trade 
the bill also creates partnerships among researchers state and 
local governments private businesses and the federal government 
for developing and selling industrial products made from farm and 
forest crops 
progress is being made for example in using corn and wheat to 
make biodegradable plastic bags and diapers soybeans are being 
experimented with in the manufacture of lubricants and printing 
ink sunflowers in fuel and red dye meadowfoam in cosmetics and 
milkweed in pillow stuffing and backpacking equipment 
