the census bureau remains determined to count 
americans but the bureau director said thursday that lagging 
public response means it will take more people and money to do it 
we plan to follow up on every housing unit for which a 
questionnaire was not returned and we have the workforce to do 
it bureau director barbara e bryant told the house census 
subcommittee 
the only thing that has changed is that our workload of 
personalvisit followup will be larger than originally planned 
to date 63 percent of households have returned the forms the 
bureau had hoped for a 70 percent return by this time 
bryant said it would take an extra 5300 workers and cost an 
additional 10 million to count each percentage point below the 70 
percent level 
a 63 percent mail response is by no means a disaster she 
said 
rep tom sawyer dohio said he was deeply troubled by the 
low level of participation so far public confidence he said may 
be shaken by reports of millions of forms that could not be 
delivered for various reasons 
we have had some operational problems and our mailresponse 
came in lower than expected we remain convinced we will have 
an accurate census bryant said 
rep thomas ridge rpa said the bureau does have problems 
but its not a crisis its not a disaster 
you cannot conclude that we will not have an accurate 
census ridge said what you can conclude is that it will cost 
a lot more money 
