<TEXT>
yugoslavias two most liberal 
republics hold elections sunday whose results could jeopardize the 
countrys fragile federation 
in croatia more than 30 parties are vying for parliamentary 
seats in the republics first multiparty elections in 50 years 
in slovenia a centerright coalition advocating independence 
hopes to consolidate power by winning the republics presidency it 
already won legislative elections 
the coalitions candidate jose pucznik faces a tough battle 
against milan kucan kucan is a popular reform communist who won 
445 percent of the vote in the first round pucnik got 266 
percent in that vote 
in croatia surveys suggest the party for democratic change 
the reformed communist party is in the lead for the legislature 
but nearly a third of the voters are undecided according to the 
polls 
if proindependence forces win in both elections it could 
exacerbate the tension with serbia that threatens to pull apart the 
country yugoslavia is a loose federation of six republics and two 
autonomous regions simmering with ethnic and ideological tensions 
slovenia and croatia already pushing for closer ties with the 
west would move further away from the hardline communist 
leadership of serbia it is the largest of yugoslavias republics 
and the only one besides montenegro still following a oneparty 
system 
croatia and slovenia have liberal judiciaries and media and 
their communist parties no longer consider their supremacy 
guaranteed in hardline serbia there is a strong communist 
influence in the press judiciary and all other aspects of life 
last week the communistdominated yugoslav military which has 
forged close ties with serbian leader slobodan milosevic warned it 
would prevent anticommunist parties in slovenia and croatia from 
assuming power 
franjo tudjman leader of the conservative croatian democratic 
union which wants radical reshaping of yugoslavia dismissed the 
statement as irrational and insane 
polls show tudjmans party in second place behind the reformed 
communists under tudjmans formula yugoslavias republics would 
be independent states that would establish relations only if common 
interests were involved 
the reform communists are more cautious they say the federation 
model is fine for now but if it fails to reflect the republics 
needs in the future yugoslavia should become a confederation 
without central rule 
the 66yearold tudjman once was the yugoslav armys youngest 
general but later spent almost five years in jail for 
counterrevolutionary activities his bid for power is fueling 
the fierce rivalry that has existed between serbia and croatia 
since yugoslavia was created in 1918 
serbias communists brand tudjman a fascist and a secessionist 
they have orchestrated several rallies of croatias 450000 serb 
minority which is haunted by memories of mass extermination in the 
croatian puppet state set up by nazi germany 
the serbs in croatia seek autonomy from the republic but all 
croatian parties oppose it 
tudjman is predicting victory but his two main rivals are also 
optimistic and appear unwilling to consider establishing a 
coalition with him if no party wins a majority 
mika tripalo a senior member of the coalition for national 
accord says tudjman is too extreme to win 
the coalition embraces five traditional croatian parties 
emerging for the first time since world war ii and almost a dozen 
other movements it has broad support 
tripalo wants some change in yugoslavias complex multiregional 
system for instance he said croatia cannot continue to spend 
vast sums on poorer regions such as serbias strifetorn province 
of kosovo 
but the coalition like the reformed communists stops short of 
advocating croatian independence both seek greater autonomy for 
the republics and a leaner federal government strictly limited to 
conducting foreign and defense policies 
ivica racan the party of democratic change leader who over the 
past six months has steered croatia to a multiparty democracy 
virtually rules out coalition with tudjman 
many voters are skeptical any party has the answer in a key area 
the economy 
all want to privatize property nationalized by the communists 
and introduce a market economy none says exactly how 
all their economic programs are vague consisting mainly of 
wishful thinking about the possibilities of huge infusions of 
foreign capital after the vote said economist tomica sohinger 
everybody seems to think that westerners have nothing better 
to do with their money than to give it to us he added 
