visitors to four of the countrys most popular 
national parks will be asked to recycle glass plastic and aluminum 
trash in a program sponsored by two chemical companies and the 
interior department 
recycling will start next month at great smoky mountains 
national park in north carolina and tennessee the first site of 
the recycling education program launched by dow chemical co 
huntsman chemical corp and the department 
acadia in maine and grand canyon in arizona will be added by 
june with plans to expand the program to californias yosemite by 
fall officials said they hoped eventually to add paper to the list 
of recycled materials 
it is time to recognize that recycling is a standard of good 
citizenship frank popoff chief executive officer of dow said 
at an openair news conference near the lincoln memorial 
bill snodgrass recycling project manager with dow said the 
first four parks were chosen for their volume of visitors a 
combined total of 18 million to 20 million a year 
its our best chance to reach the public he said we 
think americans are willing to recycle when we see people in a 
national park we think their environmental mood has to be 
fantastic 
park visitors will find special plastic bins in which to deposit 
aluminum glass and plastic trash popoff said its hoped that 
local entrepreneurs will start businesses to collect the materials 
haul them to nearby separation centers and sell them to recyclers 
where possible he said dow will arrange to have the recycled 
plastics converted and returned to the parks in the form of picnic 
tables park benches sign posts guard rails car stops and other 
products 
snodgrass said the program will cost the companies 500000 per 
park this year but the costs will decrease after the first 
startup year he said about 2 million pounds of recyclable waste 
should be recovered in the programs first year 
interior secretary manuel lujan said recycling has not been 
feasible in the past because of inadequate collection systems 
this is an experiment he said of the dowhuntsman project 
we think it will work we think its the answer 
both dow of midland mich and huntsman of salt lake city 
have inhouse recycling programs that company officials said save 
millions of dollars a year popoff said dows recycling practices 
reduce the companys wastes by 88 million pounds a year and saved 
