<TEXT>
cervical cancer deaths have dropped 11 percent in 
seven years but the death rates for black women remain more than 
twice as high as those for white women federal cancer specialists 
reported thursday 
the racial disparity is substantial and persistent the 
centers for disease control reported though black women may have 
surpassed white women in getting cervical cancer screening 
us deaths from cervical cancer dropped from 5537 in 1980 to 
4951 in 1987 the latest year for which detailed analysis is 
available the atlantabased agency said 
thats primarily from the increased use of screening said 
cdc cancer researcher eddas bennett virtually all cervical cancer 
deaths are preventable with early detection chiefly through pap 
test screening and treatment when necessary the cdc said 
overall annual cervical cancer death rates declined from 42 
deaths per 100000 women in 1980 to 34 in 1987 but while the 
rate among black women fell from 101 per 100000 in 1980 to 76 in 
1987 it remains more than twice the white rate which dropped from 
36 to 29 
the cdc attributed the racial disparity in death rates to 
generally lower socioeconomic status among blacks as well as a 
higher incidence rate of cervical cancer regardless of outcome 
preliminary cdc reports indicate that black women actually are 
more likely than whites to undergo cancerscreening pap smears 
a higher proportion of black women report having been 
screened the cdc said citing an unpublished study whose details 
are not yet publicly available 
lower screening rates for black women in previous years may be 
contributing now to higher death rates in older black women 
bennett said 
previously black women were screened less frequently than 
white women and it takes some years for it to catch up she said 
but for younger black women who were screened more frequently 
than their white counterparts disparities in followup and 
treatment may have contributed to excess cervical cancer 
mortality the cdc said 
if youre screened it often comes down to a question of 
whether you actually received the appropriate followup bennett 
said 
</TEXT>
