<TEXT>
the solidarity trade union under the gavel 
of chairman lech walesa launched its second national congress 
thursday celebrating its past triumphs while facing deep questions 
about its future 
in an emotional opening speech prime minister tadeusz 
mazowiecki invoked the memory of the unions long painful struggle 
to survive after the shock of martial law in 1981 
solidarity is alive poland is alive free and independent 
proclaimed the prime minister interrupted by cheers from the 487 
delegates 
walesa looked more to the future 
solidarity has had great achievements but expectations are 
even higher and we have to live up to them he told the congress 
before turning control of the meeting over to a 10member presidium 
the scheduled sixday meeting takes place in the same olivia 
sports hall where the union met for 18 stormy days in september and 
october 1981 
communist authorities declared military rule to crush solidarity 
only two months later forcing the union into an eightyear battle 
to regain legal status and worker rights 
the union finally triumphed at talks one year ago leading to 
the swift toppling of communist rule after elections in june 
within months communist monopolies were broken in the five other 
east bloc countries 
solidarity now faces new difficulties 
the union has managed to regain only 22 million of the 10 
million members it had in 1981 opinion polls show confidence in 
solidarity dropping as the public undergoes economic hardships 
associated with the strict austerity program pursued by 
mazowieckis solidaritycreated government 
economic restructuring is forcing plant closures and raising 
joblessness among the industrial workers who are the backbone of 
solidaritys support 
walesa meanwhile has criticized the pace of political reforms 
saying mazowieckis team is not moving quickly enough to dislodge 
communists from power in stateowned enterprises and government 
ministries 
before a backdrop upon which the red union solidarnosc logo 
was silkscreened walesa stood alone on the dais thursday morning 
and pounded his gavel three times to bring the congress to order 
delegates and hundreds of international guests and observers 
applauded with some union members raising their arms in the 
traditional solidarity vforvictory sign 
a symbolic procession of workers including blackuniformed 
miners in tall feathered caps and shipyard workers in blue 
worksuits and yellow hardhats took up positions on the side of 
the hall 
after leading the singing of the national anthem walesa 
announced that the congress had ended the underground and 
provisional phase of the unions activity 
he asked for a moment of silence for the people who died that 
we might live a dignified life 
during the congress the union will elect new leaders and accept 
a program for the future 
walesa appeared all but certain to win another term as chairman 
but rumors circulated that he would be challenged 
at least one solidarity region upper silesia is on record as 
proposing alternative candidates 
a draft prepared for the congress urges solidarity to 
concentrate more on traditional union issues while not resigning 
entirely from being a broadbased political movement 
one option to be discussed is creation of a separate solidarity 
political party 
the congress first day was mainly given over to ceremony 
procedural details and speeches from invited guests such as 
mazowiecki 
the prime minister whose economic policies are likely to come 
under harsh criticism at the congress stressed his roots in 
solidarity in an emotional speech to the congress 
i am one of you i remain one of you he said i want to 
remain faithful to this 
while acknowledging the difficult painful problems that have 
appeared unemployment hard living conditions mazowiecki 
called attention to signs of success for his economic policies 
including smothering of inflation and more goods in stores 
he said entirely free local elections scheduled across poland on 
may 27 will have a profound effect in increasing democracy in 
poland 
today he concluded 
we can say we have won this fight against totalitarianism and 
we shall will this fight for democracy 
as mazowiecki stepped away from the podium half the hall stood 
to applaud the other half remained seated until a smiling walesa 
went over to vigorously shake the prime ministers hand 
