the nations chief accident investigator asked 
on thursday for more power to examine mishaps on cruise ships that 
sail under foreign flags but work out of us ports and carry 
mostly americans 
complaining that international owners have thwarted efforts at 
investigating offshore accidents involving foreignflag cruise 
ships national transportation safety board chairman james l 
kolstad encouraged congress to expand the powers of us 
authorities 
had the scandinavian star been carrying hundreds of us 
passengers off the florida coast instead of europeans in the north 
sea neither the national transportation safety board nor the us 
coast guard would have been able to investigate this accident 
without the owners permission kolstad said 
kolstad was referring to the shipboard fire a more than a week 
ago in the north sea in which more than 160 people died 
the ntsb had investigated a major fire aboard the same ship two 
years ago in the gulf of mexico and identified some of the very 
problem areas survivors have reported this past week he told the 
house merchant marine subcommittee 
kolstad pointed to another thwarted effort at an offshore 
investigation the february 1989 collision between the celebration 
owned by miamibased carnival cruise lines and operating under 
liberian registry and a cuban bulk carrier 
not only cruise ships but also cargo ships operate under 
socalled flags of convenience such as those of panama or 
liberia allowing them to avoid higher taxes and wages the flag 
state rules govern the ship on the high seas while port 
state rules govern it within the port states territory 
but kolstad and members of congress say the burgeoning cruise 
industry has exploited the law of the seas critics say the 
businesses are american in everything except flag and many ships 
go on short excursions known as cruises to nowhere to escape 
onshore gambling laws 
unions are using the same argument to push for putting the crews 
of these ships under jurisdiction of us labor law 
opponents say that us efforts to extend regulation would 
violate longestablished international law and would drive cruise 
operators to base their ships in the bahamas and offer cheap 
flyandcruise packages 
kolstad argued that the international mechanism for addressing 
safety issues and accident investigations is too slow and 
cumbersome 
the united states is host nation to more than 80 percent of the 
worlds large passenger vessels some now capable of carrying 2600 
passengers 
