<TEXT>
the democraticcontrolled house budget 
committee on thursday approved a plan to slash president bushs 
defense spending proposal and shift billions of dollars to domestic 
programs 
the 124 trillion budget for fiscal 1991 was approved on a 
2114 partyline vote debate in the full house was scheduled for 
next week 
house majority leader richard gephardt dmo said there was 
good common sense behind the democratic version of the fiscal 
1991 budget he described it as a sharp departure from the status 
quo 
republicans portrayed the plan as an embodiment of the same old 
liberal democratic priorities with irresponsible defense cuts and 
loose reins on domestic spending but they expressed little 
concern calling the committee action just an early step in the 
long budget process 
we believe the sooner we get this exercise over the sooner 
we can actually begin writing the bill in bipartisan talks 
involving the president said rep bill frenzel of minnesota 
senior republican on the committee 
at the white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the 
president had no plans for a summit at this time on the budget 
the democratic budget envisions 295 billion in military 
spending next year about 1 billion less than in the current year 
and 8 billion less than requested by bush 
threefourths of the defense savings would be shifted 
immediately into domestic accounts that include medicaid food 
stamps education aids and antidrug abuse programs 
liberals on the committee failed thursday in their attempt to 
cut defense spending even further next year however they said 
they were satisfied with the longterm blueprint in the budget for 
squeezing the pentagon by 25 percent over the next five years 
the democratic budget is structured to force the pentagon to 
abandon procurement of expensive weapons systems although it 
avoids specifics the b2 stealth bomber is an obvious target 
the longterm focus also would help congress avert troop 
cutbacks before the november election 
the senate budget committee was scheduled to begin its 
budgetdrafting next week its chairman sen james sasser 
dtenn has suggested military spending be cut even more deeply 
next year than it would under the house plan 
senate armed services committee chairman sam nunn dga has 
balked at that suggestion 
the democratic defense cut proposal in the house is higher 
than mine would be but it is within the range of responsibility 
nunn said thursday he said he would submit his own figures late 
this week or early next week 
he proposed thursday that us troop strength in europe should 
be cut well below the 225000 baseline proposed by bush 
we should start planning on a residual force in europe on the 
order of 75000 to 100000 troops within five years he said in a 
speech 
in the house committee thursday democrats describe their fiscal 
blueprint as a turning point 
it recognizes the realities of a changing world in which our 
leadership will be tested not by the threat of nuclear war but by 
the challenge of reversing a legacy of debt and unmet needs within 
our society said budget committee chairman leon panetta dcalif 
the defense number is the fulcrum of the budget said rep 
charles schumer dny 
republicans he said wanted to maintain it to fight the last 
