<TEXT>
a new jetliner full of passengers flew 
intentionally too close to a small plane on thursday in a 
demonstration of the first collisionavoidance system to be 
approved for a commercial airliner fleet 
in a change that the airline industry says will cost it nearly 
1 billion airlines must install the traffic alert and collision 
avoidance system tcas ii in all their large jets before the end 
of 1993 
climb climb climb said an emphatic male voice generated 
by the tcas ii built into the first of 100 usair jetliners to be 
equipped this year 
a small screen in the cockpit showed a red dot indicating that 
another plane was dangerously close 
with a series of maneuvers between the small plane and the 
boeing 737400 carrying industry and government officials and 
several reporters and photographers pilots demonstrated the tcas 
ii system 
congress has ordered that onefifth of each carriers airliners 
must have the tcas ii units installed before the end of this year 
at a cost of about 125000 each 
the bill for the whole us fleet is expected to exceed 450 
million airlines put the cost at closer to 1 billion figuring in 
labor and lost profits during installation which takes about five 
days 
smaller passenger planes are required to have a less 
sophisticated version tcas i which emits traffic warnings when 
other planes come too near but does not tell the pilot what to do 
time after time the small plane came on a collision course with 
the usair jet each time the tcas screen showed the location of 
the intruding aircraft and a voice from a speaker in the cockpit 
ceiling gave quick precise instructions to the pilot beginning 
with traffic and ending with clear of conflict as 
passengers watched the small plane whiz by within a few hundred 
feet of the airliner 
if two tcas computers meet in the sky they communicate with 
each other and one pilot is told to climb and the other to 
descend said ace card bendixking program manager for tcas 
an even more sophisticated third generation of the system tcas 
iii is being developed to give pilots horizontal instructions as 
well 
honeywell has been testing such a system on an faa airliner but 
it is not expected to be approved for installation on commercial 
planes for several years 
the tcas system gives the pilot a miniature air traffic control 
system in the sky showing aircraft within a 40mile radius it can 
only detect planes with transponders that emit radar signals all 
but the smallest private planes have them 
usair officials said their 737 is the first commercial airplane 
to be equipped and certificated by the faa with the tcas unit 
northwest united and piedmont each equipped a plane with test 
versions of tcas when the system was being evaluated by the faa 
three companies manufacture tcas systems that meet faa 
specifications the ones being put on usairs fleet are made by 
alliedsignal aerospaces bendixking air transport avionics 
division 
other manufacturers are the air transport systems division of 
honeywell inc and the collins divisions of rockwell international 
the system was required as an added measure of safety for air 
travelers 
tom mcsweeney an faa official who was on the demonstration 
flight said the system would have the added benefit of making it 
easier for pilots to maintain proper separation from other aircraft 
during landings and giving them more information when they are in 
areas not covered by air traffic controllers 
the system however is seen only as a backup to faa controllers 
who monitor all flights and have responsibility for maintaining 
safe distances between aircraft particularly those the pilots 
cannot see out of the cockpit window 
</TEXT>
