<DOCNO> AP900419-0127 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a vaccine created by a pharmaceutical 
company appears to protect human immune cells from infection by the 
aids virus when the cells are in mice but a yale researcher 
cautions it may not work with people 
the vaccine called vaxsyn hiv1 was developed by microgenesys 
inc of west haven 
it has been able to defend human immune cells transplanted into 
specially bred mice while mice injected with cells from 
unvaccinated people were vulnerable to the virus officials at the 
company said wednesday 
the company said tests on people could begin soon 
dr anthony s fauci director of the national institutes of 
health aids program called the vaccine potentially a very 
important finding the test is the first evidence of protective 
immunity in humans he said 
francis black professor of epidemiology and microbiology at the 
yale school of medicine called the experiment ingenious 
saying it marks an important step toward a vaccine to prevent 
infection by the deadly virus 
but he cautioned that it does not prove that the microgenesys 
vaccine will work in people 
in humans there would be other cells that doubtless play a 
role in the progress of aids black said there are a lot of 
other differences between mice and men 
the experiment was designed to test the vaccine on cells living 
in mice to avoid the danger of infecting healthy people 
the microgenesys vaccine is composed of the outer protein coat 
of the aids virus it is made by altering the genes of caterpillar 
cells to make the protein which by itself is not dangerous or 
infectious 
franklin volvovitz president of microgenesys said healthy test 
subjects were first injected with the vaccine a type of 
infectionfighting white blood cell then was taken from the people 
and transplanted into mice bred to lack a strong immune system 
after the human immune cells called peripheral blood 
leukocytes grew in the mice the rodents were exposed to the aids 
virus volvovitz explained 
in one test 11 of the 12 mice tested were protected against the 
virus volvovitz said however all the mice given white blood 
cells from volunteers not injected with the vaccine succumbed to 
the aids virus 
the study which was reported at a symposium on acquired immune 
deficiency syndrome in colorado earlier this month was performed 
at the medical biology institute in la jolla calif a nonprofit 
laboratory funded by the federal government 
black said many scientists consider an aids vaccine impossible 
because of the complex ways in which the virus and the human immune 
system work 
i remain very optimistic that a vaccine will be developed 
he said i think they microgenesys are fairly close to a 
clinical trial 
the vaccine probably would be given to members of a population 
at high risk for aids and then rates of the disease would be 
analyzed black said 
the study would be complicated and expensive because it would 
require participation of large numbers of people he said 
the vaccine is being tested both as a measure to prevent 
infection by the aids virus and as a treatment for those already 
infected 
</TEXT>
