<TEXT>
the bush administration told congress on 
thursday that the us trade deficit after narrowing for the last 
two years could worsen in 1990 and an administration official said 
japan must do more to lower its huge trade surplus 
treasury undersecretary david mulford said japans closed 
markets pose important risks for the world economy and added 
that nations such as japan need to protect the trading system from 
protectionist onslaughts 
clearly japan has not done its part mulford told a senate 
banking subcommittee reviewing a new administration report on the 
outlook for world trade in 1990 
the report said any improvement in the trade deficit would be 
at very best modest and there was a distinct possibility the 
deficit could actually widen this year 
the report which the treasury department must prepare under the 
1988 trade law noted that the dollar has risen in value against 
the japanese yen by almost 20 percent over the last year 
a stronger dollar threatens to widen the trade deficit by making 
us goods less competitive on overseas markets and allowing 
foreign producers to lower prices to american consumers 
sen alan dixon dill said that executives of the caterpillar 
company had told him that all their efforts to improve their 
international competitiveness had been wiped out by the recent 
currency changes 
if the yen keeps falling against the dollar i dont see how 
our trade performance can be improved dixon said 
mulford said that the weakness of the yen was of a concern to 
the united states and its allies in the group of seven japan 
west germany britain france italy and canada and would be a 
primary topic on the agenda when the group next meets in early may 
in washington 
however sen paul sarbanes dmd questioned whether the g7 
countries would be able to come up with any stronger coordinated 
effort to stabilize currency rates than the bland statement issued 
when the group met earlier this month in paris 
