<TEXT>
czechoslovakia restored diplomatic relations 
with the vatican on thursday sweeping away a remnant of 40 years 
of churchstate hostility before a historic papal visit this 
weekend 
czechoslovakia joined a growing list of eastern european 
countries forging ties with the holy see in an expansion of the 
churchs influence in the once communistdominated region 
the prague government interrupted diplomatic relations in march 
1950 when it gave the papal envoy three days to leave the country 
said the vatican in a statement 
the vatican hailed the resumption of ties as bringing an end to 
the sad parenthesis of these last 40 years 
pope john paul iis visit saturday and sunday to czechoslovakia 
will be his first to a warsaw pact country other than his native 
poland 
the trip symbolizes everything that has happened in the 
countries of what is by now the excommunist world said the 
vatican newspaper losservatore romano 
under a succession of hardline communist regimes that ruled 
until czechoslovakias peaceful revolution last november such a 
visit was unthinkable 
as elsewhere in the soviet bloc organized religion in 
czechoslovakia was rigidly controlled believers were repressed and 
religious education was severely restricted 
in his inauguration speech dec 29 president vaclav havel who 
had been jailed by the communist regime asked the pope to visit 
prague as a goodwill gesture to support the democratic changes 
sweeping eastern europe 
poland last year reestablished diplomatic relations with the 
vatican followed by hungary in february a month ago the vatican 
and the soviet union established official ties for the first time 
since the russian revolution although they fall short of full 
diplomatic relations 
the vatican has also restored the leadership of the church in 
romania and diplomatic ties with bucharest are believed not far off 
the announcement at the vatican and in prague said relations 
were being renewed on the level of a czechoslovak embassy and an 
apostolic nunciature 
the envoys were not immediately named 
the vatican estimates that a little more than half of 
czechoslovakias 155 million people are roman catholics 
on several occasions john paul had deplored the sad state 
of the church in czechoslovakia where up to 10 of the countrys 13 
dioceses were left without bishops the church is led by 
90yearold cardinal frantisek tomasek who long struggled for 
church freedoms 
soon after the regime led by milos jakes was toppled relations 
with rome warmed in recent months the vatican has returned the 
church hierarchy to full strength 
millions of catholics are expected to attend the papal events in 
prague the shrine city of velehrad and bratislava during the 
twoday visit the first by a pope to czechoslovakia 
the trip will be the 46th foreign tour of john pauls papacy 
trips by john paul to poland and hungary are scheduled next year 
