epa officials cautioned that they are unable from the raw 
figures the latest available to assess the health risks to 
individuals the data do not take into account levels of toxicity 
release concentrations and actual exposure 
nevertheless federal officials have been surprised at the high 
volume of releases of toxic chemicals in both 1987 when 5 billion 
pounds of pollution was reported and 1988 the reporting 
requirement covers 332 toxic chemicals 
the figures are absolutely shocking declared rep gerry 
sikorksi dminn who along with several other members of congress 
obtained a special computer run on the epa figures and provided 
additional details about the releases 
among the chemicals routinely emitted from industrial sources 
were 77 carcinogens the most widely released cancercausing 
chemical 115 million pounds was dichloromethane a chemical 
often used as an industrial solvent and paint stripper 
industry released a total of 281 million pounds of carcinogens 
including chemicals such as arsenic benzene and vinyl chloride 
weve got to bring these pollution numbers down epa 
administrator william reilly said as he released the latest data 
cleanair legislation that already has passed the senate and is 
being considered in the house would impose stringent controls on 
toxic industrial chemicals and require companies to use the best 
available technology to curb releases 
under current law the epa is required to deal with each 
chemical separately in more than a decade it has placed controls 
on only eight of the hundreds of toxic chemicals in use many of 
the chemicals however are subject to local and state regulation 
the releases reported by industry however are legal and within 
federal standards officials said 
chemical and allied industries accounted for about half of the 
total releases two states with a concentration of petrochemical 
plants louisiana and texas accounted for more than onefourth 
of the pollution totals 
the toxic pollution figures reflect data provided the epa by 
19762 industrial plants nationwide it is the second year such 
reports have been provided under a new citizen righttoknow law 
the epa announcement provided only general release statistics 
and no information on specific plants 
but information released by sikorski from data contained on epa 
computer tapes showed that amax magnesium co of rowley utah had 
by far the highest volume of releases into the air nearly 110 
million pounds 
amax was followed among the top five industrial air polluters in 
1988 by tennessee eastman co kingsport tenn 40 million pounds 
avtex fibers in front royal va 34 million pounds triad 
chemical donaldsonville la 27 million pounds and eastman kodak 
co rochester ny 216 million pounds 
the avtex fibers plant in virginia closed last november after a 
lengthy battle with the state over pollution issues 
the states with the largest volume of toxic chemical releases 
overall were louisiana 716 million pounds texas 596 million 
pounds ohio 229 million pounds florida 226 million pounds 
indiana 213 million pounds and tennessee 203 million pounds 
according to the epa 
more than half of the toxic releases 243 billion pounds went 
into the air while the remainder was disposed of in surface water 
stored in landfills or injected into underground wells more than 
half of the air pollutants were reported by the petrochemical 
rubber plastics and primary metals industries 
industrial plants released 360 million pounds of toxic chemicals 
into lakes streams and rivers and disposed of 560 million pounds 
in onsite landfills about 122 billion pounds of chemicals were 
injected deep into underground wells for storage 
another 570 million pounds of toxic chemicals were transferred 
to municipal wastewater treatment plants for processing and an 
additional 11 billion pounds of chemicals were turned over for 
treatment and disposal at special offsite facilities or storage 
sites the epa said 
neither the chemicals sent to the municipal plants nor those 
sent elsewhere for treatment and disposal were counted by the epa 
in its overall release figure agency spokesman sean mcelheny said 
it is assumed most of those chemicals are treated and not released 
into the environment 
however the epa has in the past criticized many municipal 
treatment facilities for not adequately ensuring that industrial 
wastes are kept from being released into surface waters neither 
the private or municipal treatment facilities subject to the toxic 
release reporting requirements 
</TEXT>
