<TEXT>
the government won a surprisingly easy victory 
thursday night in a crucial vote on a bill to give british 
passports and citizenship to an estimated 225000 hong kong 
residents 
the 650seat house of commons approved the measure by a vote of 
313216 despite rare opposition from both rightwingers in the 
governing conservative party opposed to increased immigration and 
from the socialist labor party which called the bill elitist 
the measure now goes to committee for possible amendments and 
then back to the house of commons where political observers say its 
passage is virtually assured it then must pass the unelected house 
of lords 
the government says it hopes the bill will become law by summer 
the 97vote margin of victory in the latest vote was far higher 
than political commentators predicted 
home secretary david waddington had argued that giving british 
citizenship to 50000 key hong kong residents and their families 
would prevent a braindrain and maintain confidence in the colony 
before it reverts to china in 1997 
the vote on the british nationality hong kong bill was seen as 
one of the toughest tests for prime minister margaret thatcher 
since she took power nearly 11 years ago because of the prospect 
of a conservative revolt and labor opposition 
the opposition labor party told its members to vote against it 
on grounds that only hong kongs elite will be given passports 
smaller opposition parties were divided on the bill 
an initial analysis of the vote showed 44 conservatives voting 
against the government and one labor member voting for the 
government the number of labor lawmakers voting against the 
government was not immediately available 
the voting capped an acrimonious and noisy debate in the commons 
under the bill 50000 hong kong residents in good jobs 
earning good salaries would be selected on a point system from a 
wide variety of fields to receive british passports waddington 
said 
first and foremost this is not an immigration bill he 
said this is a nationality bill designed to anchor people to 
hong kong rather than to encourage them to come here 
in an angry retort former conservative party chairman norman 
tebbit called for the bill to be thrown out he warned that it 
could lead to rising racial tension and accused the thatcher 
government of reneging on election pledges against largescale 
immigration 
these pledges were made because these islands of ours are 
already overcrowded and in the belief that great waves of 
immigration by people who do not share our culture our language 
our ways of social conduct in many cases who owe no allegiance to 
our culture was and is a destablizing factor in society he 
said 
labors deputy leader roy hattersley objected to the bill 
saying the only solution that meets the needs of all the people 
is to make major progress toward democracy in the colony 
but paddy ashdown leader of the centrist liberal democrats 
asked whether hattersley had not learned anything from the chinese 
government crackdown on prodemocracy demonstrators in beijing last 
spring 
what democracy needs to be supported by is the right of 
those people to leave if they wish with a british passport and come 
to britain 
about 325 million hong kong chinese now hold a special category 
of british passport that do not confer a right to residence in 
britain 
