<TEXT>
a majority of large banks responding to a 
survey said they had tightened their lending practices for real 
estate loans in the last six months federal reserve chairman alan 
greenspan said 
greenspan said the federal reserve which regulates bank holding 
companies had surveyed 60 of the countrys largest banks in 
january to determine whether it was easier or harder for businesses 
to obtain credit 
a large majority of the banks said they had become less 
willing to make construction and land development loans during the 
past six months greenspan said in written responses released 
thursday by the senate banking committee 
greenspan did not provide a specific percentage figure but said 
that most banks responding to the survey also had tightened 
standards for making mergerrelated loans or loans to businesses 
with lower credit ratings 
onefifth of the banks said they were less willing to make 
general business loans greenspan said 
the banks blamed the tighter credit policies primarily on the 
economys weakness late last year which made them scrutinize loan 
requests more carefully other factors cited by the banks were 
rising numbers of bad loans and closer scrutiny by banking 
regulators 
many small and mediumsized businesses have complained they are 
facing a severe credit crunch at present as financial institutions 
are forced to tighten credit practices under pressure from federal 
regulators who have become more strict in the wake of the giant 
savings and loan bailout 
greenspans comments came in response to a question submitted by 
sen john f kerry dmass who said many businesses in his state 
were complaining about their inability to get credit 
greenspan said the fed was aware that banks in new england and 
other areas of the country had tightened their lending standards 
he said such a development could have an impact on overall economic 
activity in a region 
but he said for the lending slowdown to pose serious threats to 
the health of the economy it would need to be more severe than what 
the fed has detected and extend for a longer period of time 
greenspan said it was essential for banks to meet the financing 
needs of their communities but in a prudent manner 
as recent experience has shown there are substantial costs 
associated with both too much restraint and with too little he 
said we federal regulators are attempting to strike the proper 
balance 
