<TEXT>
federal officials thursday proposed 64 million 
in fines against phillips 66 co and a contractor in connection 
with a texas chemical plant explosion that killed 23 workers and 
injured 124 last october 
the proposed fines of 567 million against phillips and 
729600 against fish engineering and construction inc would be 
the second largest for a single inspection by the federal 
occupational health and safety administration 
osha accused phillips of 566 willful violations and nine serious 
violations at the houston chemical complex in suburban pasadena 
the agency accused fish engineering a maintenence contractor at 
the plant of 181 willful violations 12 serious violations and one 
of mismanaging records 
a series of explosions oct 23 destroyed the section of the 
plant that makes polyethylene which is used to make plastics 
twentythree workers were killed and 124 were hurt 
we conducted an extensive investigation of what caused this 
catastrophe said gilbert saulter oshas southwest regional 
administrator 
he said the agency determined that the explosion would not have 
occurred had phillips provided a safe workplace by following 
osha and industry standards 
phillips and fish engineering have 15 days to contest the fines 
at no time has phillips ever compromised the safety of its 
employees the company said in a statement based on 
preliminary information we do plan to contest a number of the 
citations and we do take issue with osha characterizing any of the 
violations as willful acts 
phillips 66 is the chemical production and marketing arm of 
phillips petroleum co 
fish engineering said in a statement that it also would contest 
the fines 
however the statement said oshas investigation confirmed 
that the houston contractor did not cause or contribute to the 
explosion 
saulter said one of the major problems at the plant included the 
lack of a doublevalve system as a failsafe on gas emissions 
phillips officials have said the explosion occurred after a seal 
on a polyethylene reactor ruptured leaking highly flammable 
ethylene and isobutane gas from a pipeline it was unclear what 
ignited the gas 
workers reported that only a few seconds elapsed between the 
time they spotted a cloud of gas heard warning sirens and were 
rocked by explosions 
saulter said the deficiencies described as willful violations 
fell into three categories failure to prevent the release of 
flammable vapors failure to minimize or mitigate the consequences 
of a release and failure to provide adequate fire protection 
the serious violations include inadequate emergency exits and 
emergency planning inaudible emergency alarm sire and deficiencies 
in hazard communications and respiratory protection programs 
phillips petroleum president glenn cox said the companys 
investigation showed the explosion was the result of a departure 
from established routine procedures 
we are thoroughly evaluating our procedures and training to 
determine how the possibility for error can be further minimized 
cox said in a statement issued from company headquarters in 
bartlesville okla 
saulter said phillips officials already have contacted osha 
about the reconstruction of the plant and possible modifications at 
the site but declined to give specifics of the talks 
he said labor secretary elizabeth dole is expected to give 
president bush a report in the coming weeks about the accident 
what should be done at the new plant and what changes might be 
needed at other plants across the country 
the largest fine ever sought by osha was proposed last november 
when the government said it was seeking 73 million from usx corp 
for 2000 alleged safety violations at a steel plant near 
pittsburgh and another on the pennsylvania side of the delaware 
river near trenton nj usx has contested the fine 
