<TEXT>
state lawmakers broke a deadlock thursday 
on school financing that would raise teachers salaries ending a 
strike that idled classes for more than 300000 students this week 
as striking teachers crowded the halls of the capitol and 
thousands more rallied outside senators approved an emergency 
clause on a 230 million education reform and tax bill shortly 
before 6 pm the bill was sent to gov henry bellmon who said he 
would sign the bill at an undetermined date 
the emergency clause which allows the bill to become law as 
soon as it is signed had been a stumbling block to the package 
the senate failed last week to pass it prompting the oklahoma 
education association to call for a fiveday teacher walkout 
the bill calls for spending 681 million to raise minimum 
teacher salaries by 1500 a year for four years the bill would 
not increase the salaries of teachers above the minimums but 212 
million budgeted for schools could be used for teacher salaries and 
other items 
oklahoma teachers rank 48th in pay among the states making an 
average of 22000 a year the national average is 29648 in 
oklahoma the minimum beginning teachers salary with a bachelor 
degree is 15060 
a new day is dawning for education in oklahoma bellmon said 
after the vote oklahoma will no longer take a back seat among 
the states where education is concerned from now on others can 
look to oklahoma for leadership in education 
union officials said the passage would end the walkout which 
was in its fourth day thursday it was unclear if regular classes 
would held friday 
teachers in districts already closed for the week planned to 
hold a thank you rally at the capitol on friday said nancy 
jewell spokeswoman for the oklahoma education association 
thousands of teachers as well as some administrators parents 
and students protested earlier thursday over the legislative 
stalemate on a bill that calls for raising the state sales tax and 
increasing personal and corporate income taxes to pay for the 
education reforms 
a halfcent increase in the 4cent state sales tax increase 
would raise 104 million as would a 10 percent increase in 
personal income taxes an increase in the corporate tax from 5 
percent to 6 percent would produce 22 million 
a compromise that would give tax rebates to lowincome families 
led to the passage of the emergency clause as the vote on the 
clause was announced shortly before 6 pm a loud cheer broke out 
in the senate gallery 
the need to resolve the stalemate had taken on an added urgency 
after senate president pro tempore bob cullison a democrat said 
he might adjourn the special session thursday effectively killing 
the measure 
senate appropriations chairman stratton taylor a democrat 
earlier brought cheers from protesting teachers when he told a 
rally of more than 10000 that democratic senators were meeting and 
might have a solution after a day of closed caucuses 
the oklahoma education association which called for the walkout 
last week said 145 school districts in the state were closed 
thursday among those were tulsa oklahoma city and lawton the 
three largest districts in the state with about 95000 students 
state education officials have said the walkout has affected 
about 60 percent or 343200 of the states 572000 students have 
been affected the state has 606 school districts 
some schools have remained open throughout the week while 
others have been closed the entire time in some instances parents 
and businessmen have made the trek to the capitol while teachers 
have stayed in the classroom 
the oea represents 31000 of the states estimated 35000 
teachers 
the democratic majority apparently was not involved in any 
negotiations with republicans who voted against the education 
reform and tax bill earlier causing the stalemate 
thursdays demonstrators undaunted by rain and soggy grounds 
staged the most boisterous rally of the week 
sen taylor touched off a round of chants that echoed through 
the capitol area when he proposed a new motto never last again 
i dont believe the people of oklahoma want to be at the 
bottom of the heap in salaries or educational funding said 
house speaker steve lewis who is the principal author of the 
education package 
</TEXT>
