<TEXT>
no criminal charges will be filed in 
the february drowning deaths of three teenagers from a probation 
camp who fell into an icy lake and four men who tried to rescue 
them prosecutors said 
mono county district attorney stan eller said in a memo to the 
sheriff tuesday that he felt there was insufficient evidence to 
prosecute the camps operator camp oneal inc or any individual 
three juvenile offenders housed at camp oneal fell through thin 
ice and drowned during an outing to frigid convict lake in the 
sierra nevada on feb 19 two counselors and two other adults 
drowned trying to save them 
although the district attorneys investigation clears the camp 
operator of criminal wrongdoing a civil complaint filed by the 
state department of social services is still pending 
the complaint alleges inadequate supervision leading to the 
drownings sexual misconduct overmedicating the juvenile offenders 
and not properly maintaining medical records a hearing is 
scheduled for aug 16 
the group home licensed by the state to treat emotionally 
troubled youths has been closed since the complaint was filed 
march 16 
camp oneal had been cited before the convict lake tragedy for 
several violations of state licensing standards according to 
department of social services spokeswoman kathleen norris 
the camps director bobbi trott has denied any wrongdoing in 
the drownings or other alleged incidents at the camp 
</TEXT>
