<DOCNO> AP900419-0171 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a government plan to give the roman 
catholic church a television channel has created strong opposition 
in a nation where the church worked closely with a halfcentury 
dictatorship overthrown 16 years ago 
prime minister anibal cavaco silvas plan would provide the 
church not just a platform for religious opinions but a full 
commercial franchise for one of two private channels that are to 
end a 26year state monopoly on television 
it has provoked heated debate of the churchs place in a society 
that still retains considerable anticlerical feeling from the 
revolution by leftist military officers on april 25 1974 
conservative businessmen among the centerright premiers 
staunchest supporters have joined the left against the plan 
even the church is not happy the catholic bishops conference 
also wants control of evening programming on one of the two state 
channels and extended air time on weekends 
the debate has split cavaco silvas social democratic party 
which faces elections next year to preserve its parliamentry 
majority 
i think it is immoral to grant a channel without a public 
tender said franciso pinto balsemao once a social democratic 
premier and now a media executive his company is a leading 
contender for one of the private channels 
leftists and liberals worry about the political impact of church 
television and recall the roman catholic hierarchys close 
cooperation with the dictatorial regime founded by antonio oliveira 
salazar 
salazar granted the church a radio station radio renascenca in 
1936 the stations management is leading the church campaign for a 
television channel 
when cavaco silva liberalized radio broadcasting last year he 
restricted private stations to local transmission but left 
renascenca as portugals only national station not under state 
control 
renascenca has very strong political views and they interfere 
a lot pinto balsemao the former prime minister told the 
associated press we cannot say it is an independent project 
since the 1974 revolution the church has entered politics in 
unsuccessful efforts to stop leftist governments from liberalizing 
divorce laws and legalizing abortion 
church leaders organized a long and emotional campaign against 
abortion in the early 1980s with the support of the social 
democrats and conservative parties a parliamentary majority of 
socialists and communists legalized abortion in 1984 
moises espirito santo a sociologist at lisbons new university 
specializing in religious affairs said he doubted the church could 
enlist as much support for the television channel as it had against 
abortion 
the church today has more political power than it had under 
salazar but this lacks the emotion of the abortion issue he 
said in an interview 
more than 96 percent of portuguese are roman catholic but 
figures published recently in the newspaper o jornal indicate only 
27 percent attend mass regularly 
strength of religious feeling varies widely the report said 
about 65 percent of people in northern minho province go to church 
regularly but the number dips below 5 percent in the southern 
alentejo the rural stronghold of the communist party 
espirito santo said much of portugals popular religious 
feeling particularly in the countryside is based on traditional 
beliefs and less influenced by teachings of the bishops in the 
cities 
efforts by clerics to sway votes may have helped thwart 
communist ambitions immediately after the revolution but increased 
political awareness after 16 years of democracy means few people 
now follow their priests political guidance he said 
the church no longer has any electoral weight espirito 
santo declared its influence lies in the links the bishops have 
with politicians 
some catholics wonder whether the church will compromise its 
moral standards by entering the materialistic world of tv 
advertising and competition with the racy brazilian soap operas 
portuguese viewers enjoy 
what sort of commercial television can they have pinto 
balsemao asked what sort of advertising can they accept are 
they going to have dallas and dynasty and the brazilian 
telenovelas soap operas which are full of sex and beautiful 
almostnaked girls 
fernando magalhaes crespo director of radio renascenca said 
moral standards would be maintained 
it will be a television with programs parents wont be ashamed 
to watch with their children he told balsemaos weekly newspaper 
expresso 
magalhaes crespo said dallas and falcon crest britains 
benny hill and many of the brazilian soaps were not likely to 
appear on the catholic channel 
espirito santo said the argument over telvision is the latest in 
a long line of disputes dating to the 19th century when conflicts 
between clerical and secular political groups sometimes became 
bloody 
roman catholicism was the state religion until 1910 when an 
anticlerical revolution overthrew the monarchy and founded the 
republic 
</TEXT>
