<TEXT>
when dawn breaks over the alleghany 
mountains and shines dimly on stonewall jackson barracks cadets in 
gray and black uniforms march to the mess hall in a cadence 
unchanged by the passing of 150 years 
tradition is the lifeblood of virginia military institute a 
small public college defending its maleonly admissions policy from 
a lawsuit by the federal government what some graduates call the 
second war of northern aggression 
the first skirmish in the sexdiscrimination lawsuit will be may 
4 in us district court in roanoke 
the us justice department claims vmis admissions policy is a 
chauvinistic anachronism that is unconstitutional and violates the 
civil rights act 
we believe the justice department is wrong and we intend to 
fight said maj gen john knapp vmi superintendent 
the vast majority of cadets and alumni believe admitting women 
to the corps would ruin the schools mission of producing 
citizensoldiers 
the academic training and the strict honor code would remain 
they say but the camaraderie achieved through living in close 
quarters and surviving a grueling physical and psychological 
freshman year would be changed forever 
the 1300 cadets all live in a threestory fortresslike 
dormitory the spartan rooms have no telephones posters 
television sets curtains or locks on the doors and the 
standardized cots shelves and desks are made of bare wood 
the cadets awake to reveille at 655 am and head to communal 
showers 
women they say just wouldnt fit in 
how could a cadet bust into the room of a lady at any time and 
order her to do pushups asked antonio zang a cadet from 
fairfax were taught here to be gentlemen how can you yell at a 
lady and still be a gentleman 
the lawsuit was prompted by a letter from a northern virginia 
teenage girl who complained that she could not attend the school 
vmi and the citadel in charleston sc are the only 
statesupported military schools in the nation that refuse to admit 
women the justice department is investigating the citadel for a 
possible sexdiscrimination case 
ironically virginias first female attorney general mary sue 
terry is defending vmi in the lawsuit which also names as 
defendants gov douglas wilder the nations first black elected 
governor and the state system of higher education 
</TEXT>
