<TEXT>
june romeo is back at kent state a generation 
after witnessing national guard bullets kill four students and 
wound nine more the tears still come easily 
its funny the 38yearold nursing instructor and graduate 
student said they said 13 seconds of gunfire when you stop to 
think one two three four if you count thats a long time 
romeo then an 18yearold freshman from westlake ohio was 
about 20 steps from one of the wounded tom grace you dont 
believe it at first she said no one had ever shot a student 
protester before 
the violence and its emotioncharged aftermath became too much 
for romeo she left campus the next year upset by such scenes as a 
cafeteria confrontation between students joking about the shootings 
and others who were irate 
it was not the right place for me said romeo who tried 
selling insurance then enrolled at baldwinwallace college a small 
liberal arts school in berea near her hometown 
i kept thinking i should go back but i never did said 
romeo who keeps a candle from the first campus anniversary 
memorial may 4 1971 twenty years later she has come back as a 
graduate student and instructor in educational theory 
the tragedy was very personal said romeo whose 
undergraduate students occasionally note her resemblance to the 
young woman whose searing photographic image arms raised high over 
a dying kent state student won a pulitzer prize 
romeo said she pushed the shootings out of her mind along with 
other campus memories she lost track of classmates and roommates 
she collected but never read almost every book about the 
shootings and student unrest in 1970 
i wanted things connected with it she said of the books 
her husband has read the books but the two dont talk about may 
4 
romeo says the only person with whom she discussed kent state in 
detail was a physician and former navy officer who convinced her 
that the guardsmen would never have fired without a command 
that more than anything else has bothered me i cant 
conceive of a mind that would give an order like that she said 
pausing to catch her breath at the thought 
romeos emotions were rekindled four years ago when james 
rhodes who as ohio governor had ordered the national guard onto 
the kent state campus to restore order was a patient at the 
cleveland clinic where romeo was a nurse 
the softspoken romeo said her loathing for rhodes and his role 
in what happened was so strong that she took a day or two off while 
rhodes was hospitalized 
i kept thinking i want so much for him to feel some of the 
terror those people felt she said that really brought it 
back i never had feelings like that about anyone i really cant 
think of people i hate 
romeo returned to kent state fulltime last year she credits 
her social activism for her return to campus and her efforts to 
deal with memories of the shootings she runs a program in 
clevelands inner city that teaches youngsters to read and write as 
well as how to make reasoned decisions that will affect their lives 
i need to help people become aware she said aware of 
choices and consequences 
romeo believes that few among the couple thousand kent state 
students protesting the war on may 4 1970 were aware of the 
potential consequences she teaches her students that youre 
going to have to decide for yourselves what battles are important 
to fight and what arent worth your time and effort 
when her students learn she was a student of the 70s they are 
curious about the period she tells them she favored weird 
clothes and wore her hair long and flowing 
i even wore flowers in my hair she tells them they said 
noooo 
romeo brushes aside the current campus brouhaha over whether the 
granite memorial to be dedicated on the 20th anniversary of the 
shootings is too little too late 
i dont care that much about the memorial she said i 
think the most fitting thing is to keep the whole thing alive 
people 20 years down the line should really be questioning it it 
should be studied like we study wars 
