<TEXT>
twenty years later the survivors mostly 
poor peasants still remember the terror of the american warplanes 
and the many who could not evade their fury 
hok nhem says the planes killed four of her 10 children and 
destroyed her fine concrete house two youngsters died at play in a 
village street two older children were felled by strafing jets in 
the rice paddies 
to this very day i dont know why the americans bombed our 
village said choi sandal she recalls the afternoon when six 
jets swooped down and she sprinted home from the fields to try to 
save her grandparents but was held back by flames shooting as high 
as the coconut trees 
for five years in a brutal aerial bombardment kept secret from 
the american public us planes often b52 bombers savaged the 
countryside around this remote town and other border areas of 
eastern cambodia 
in the spring of 1970 american soldiers came on foot president 
richard nixon ordered the invasion to finally destroy border 
sanctuaries used by vietnamese communists 
to protect our men who are in vietnam and to guarantee the 
continued success of our withdrawal and vietnamization program i 
have concluded that the time has come for action nixon announced 
on television april 30 1970 a day earlier american and south 
vietnamese troops had begun operation total victory 
the invasion prompted antiwar demonstrations across the united 
states at kent state university in ohio four students were shot 
dead by national guardsmen 
in cambodia some historians say the invasion was the catalyst 
for a chain reaction of national tragedies villagers here dont 
make such subtle linkages they do say that since that time they 
have known only suffering 
the pattern of vietnam is being repeated said an associated 
press dispatch from the front the american troops are putting 
the torch to homes because they may be useful to the communists 
livestock is shot for the same reason 
some of the worst damage was inflicted on snuol and mimot 
described by the americans as an enemy hub snuol was all but 
razed when troops entered the once picturesque town they found the 
charred bodies of one girl one woman and two men 
mimot was partly destroyed by air strikes after north vietnamese 
in the town fired on us helicopters it is pretty well blown 
away reported one american officer 
today ox carts roll down the towns red dirt main street past 
buildings still scarred by shrapnel long strips of twostory 
shophouses were rebuilt only in the last several years said 
deputy district chief rin saman 
rin saman who was in mimot during the invasion said the bombed 
sugar factory where he worked remains inoperative and much of the 
vast rubber plantation on the edge of town still lies in ruins 
only traces remain of what was a hospital for plantation workers 
by the end of june 1970 the invasion force of 63000 including 
23000 americans had returned to south vietnam according to the 
us command 339 americans 799 south vietnamese and more than 
11000 communist soldiers were killed and vast amounts of communist 
supplies destroyed in the operation 
but cambodia would never heal the invasion had created a new 
battle front dragged all of cambodia into the indochinese 
conflict and started years of national agony 
the capital city of phnom penh as well as the usbacked 
government of lon nol fell to the khmer rouge guerrillas april 17 
1975 two weeks before the fall of saigon what followed was the 
ghastly ultrarevolution of the victors 
mimots inhabitants were driven into rural communes or forced 
into slave labor on the rubber plantation press samoeur deputy 
governor of kompong cham province which surrounds mimot estimates 
360000 inhabitants of the province perished under the 197578 rule 
of khmer rouge leader pol pot some say craters from the b52 
bombings were used for mass graves 
nationwide estimates of deaths by execution starvation and 
disease in the killing fields of pol pot range as high as 3 
million in a country that had 73 million inhabitants in 1975 
it was harder to survive under pol pot than under american 
bombs said rin saman 
in 1978 the area was invaded again this time by the vietnamese 
who punched across the border on christmas day to oust the khmer 
rouge today the khmer rouge are onethird of an antigovernment 
coalition supported by the united states 
us aggressors bombed schools roads bridges hospitals 
markets they razed peoples homes they sprayed chemicals on the 
rubber plantations press samoeur said in an interview and 
until this day the us government still has a distorted view of 
what is happening in cambodia 
choi sandal now 38 is still haunted by the sight of her 
grandparents charred remains in the stillsmoldering village 
where only one of 60 houses survived the aerial attack 
the aging widow hok nhem posed for a photo before a house built 
on the ruins of the concrete one only one pillar remains of the 
old atop which she has placed an aviary for doves 
other survivors joined them talking openly with this reporter 
the first american most had met in 20 years a toothless old man 
was overheard suggesting the reporter might be there to assess 
damage for future us reparations 
but nobody openly mentioned this nor exhibited the slightest 
hostility instead they clasped their hands together in the 
traditional prayerlike gesture of farewell and offered a glass 
of sweet coconut milk 
</TEXT>
