<TEXT>
every spring just as surely as the 
daffodils sad memories bloom again 
in the spring of 1970 in his last letter home from college 
william schroeder altered a few lines from a popular neil young 
song i am a child to tell his mother he loved her and savored 
weekends spent at home 
i am a child i last awhile 
you cant perceive all the pleasure in my smile 
you make the rules you say whats fair 
its lots of fun to have you there 
twenty springs have come and gone since may 4 1970 when 
william schroeder and three other students were gunned down by 
national guardsmen at antiwar demonstrations on the kent state 
university campus 
but the annual arrival of spring cannot erase the pain felt for 
missing sons and daughters for friends lost forever for 
graduations unattended and anniversaries uncelebrated 
even after 20 years it still hurts said florence schroeder 
who lives in lorain they took him away but they cant wipe out 
the memory 
schroeders mother can still recite her voice breaking the 
words from the neil young song but sometimes the memories are too 
painful for her and her husband louis 
at the end of the trials she said we promised ourselves 
wed never go that far down deep into our souls again it hurts too 
much 
schroeder 19 was shot in the back while lying on the ground 
he took cover when the gunfire began as he walked to class after a 
meeting with his rotc adviser 
he was concerned that the military program paying his 
scholarship might be discontinued because demonstrators had burned 
down the rotc building two days earlier the vietnam war tormented 
schroeder his mother said because he knew he would end up there 
flowers and bullets is the name of an album of remembrances 
put together for allison krauses parents by her college boyfriend 
on her tombstone is the epitaph flowers are better than bullets 
may 3 1970 
may 3 a sunday provided a sunny peaceful respite from campus 
rumblings as allison a freshman honors student from pittsburgh 
who had just turned 19 and her boyfriend strolled the campus they 
encountered a soldier with a lilac in his gun barrel 
when his commanding officer ridiculed him and pulled the lilac 
from the rifle allison grabbed it before he could toss it down as 
the officer walked away allison yelled after him 
whats the matter with peace flowers are better than 
bullets 
her father arthur krause spent a decade seeking the justice he 
and the other kent families as they came to call themselves 
felt was due them 
in the final court settlement of a 40 million civil suit in 
january 1979 the four families and nine wounded students received 
675000 to be divided among them but more important to them they 
said was a signed statement of regret and acknowledgment from ohio 
gov james a rhodes and 27 guardsmen that the shootings should not 
have occurred 
arthur krause died of cancer in 1988 his widow doris feels 
only rancor toward kent state she says she will never return under 
any official invitation not even for dedication of a memorial that 
will mark the 20th anniversary of her daughters slaying 
ill be bitter to the day i die mrs krause said she 
recalls with anger how she learned of allisons death only by 
calling the hospital after a reporter told her allison had been 
wounded 
would you not expect to hear something from that university 
she asked would you not expect to see an official at the 
hospital where you went to see your dead child to extend a hand to 
tell you what happened 
theyve never done that their letter of sympathy was a check 
a refund made out to allison for spring tuition she wasnt around 
to cash it 
jeff miller left behind an antiwar poem he wrote when he was 16 
a teenager from a small ohio farm clutches his side in 
pain 
and as he feels his life ebbing away he too asks why 
why is he dying here thousands of miles from home 
the war without a purpose marches on relentlessly 
not stopping to mourn for its dead 
content to wait for its end 
but all the frightened parents who still have their sons 
fear that the end is not in sight 
four years later he lay dying in a pool of blood a bullet 
through his skull it was his body that a 14yearold runaway mary 
ann vecchio knelt over in the famous photograph her arms 
outstretched in anguish her face filled with terror 
his mother elaine holstein of new york city is still shaken by 
his poem 
its always struck me as strange and ironic that he refers to 
a teenager from a small ohio farm she said never knowing 
that he himself would die four years later in a small ohio farm 
town 
among the mementos sarah and martin scheuer of boardman ohio 
have kept for 20 years is an anniversary card from their younger 
daughter 20yearold sandra 
her note had urged them to dine at a chinese restaurant and 
enjoy their 27th wedding anniversary that may 4 honorable wish 
for happy anniversary to honorable couple who still have big yen 
for each other 
but celebration turned to mourning the card arrived the same 
day sandy lay dead in a parking lot felled by a bullet through her 
neck as she walked to a speech therapy class 
how would you like to identify your child in a morgue mrs 
scheuer asked 20 years later 
