unless the killings cause an uproar abroad nothing gets 
done said a judge who for a time was dealing with the case of 
seven young men slain nov 18 a witness said they were lined up 
against a wall and shot by soldiers 
no witness or complainant came forward by the end of november 
and the judge referred the case to the next higher justice 
coming forward to testify would be a real risk the judge 
said the case will be under investigation until it is 
forgotten 
the young men were killed in the poor cuscatancingo neighborhood 
of san salvador two days after troopers of the elite ustrained 
atlacatl battalion massacred six jesuit priests who taught at 
central american university their housekeeper and her daughter 
those killings shocked the world the united states which gives 
el salvador more than 1 million a day in aid put pressure on the 
cristiani administration to identify and punish the people 
responsible 
a colonel and three lieutenants have been charged but critics 
say others were involved 
such charges are an exception in a country where members of the 
armed forces or militarybacked death squads are believed to have 
murdered thousands of people they suspect of being leftists 
despite a wealth of evidence no officer has been convicted of a 
crime involving politically motivated abuse of human rights in el 
salvador 
no officer had even been charged until march 1989 when a major 
was indicted for killings he has not been tried 
the attention given the jesuit case is exceptional the 
treatment of the cuscatancingo case has become the norm in a decade 
of civil war 
as long as our military men do not understand the meaning of 
the administration of justice and that they too are subject to 
it we will have no justice and no improvement in respect for 
human rights said maria julia hernandez director of the roman 
catholic church legal aid office 
the cuscatancingo killings were barely noticed during an 
offensive by leftist guerrillas that convulsed san salvador and 
three other cities for two weeks 
attorney general mauricio colorado who has dealt with dozens of 
foreign officials checking on the jesuit investigation said he had 
not even heard of the case 
there were a hundred cases like that of bodies found in the 
street colorado said when told of it he suggested the victims 
were guerrillas or were killed in a cross fire 
the seven bodies were found sprawled at the foot of a 
bloodstained wall the only wall on the street pocked by bullets 
two victims still clutched social security cards in their hands in 
what the witness described as an effort to identify themselves as 
workmen 
colorado acknowledged that us pressure has spurred some 
investigations and said justice should work for everybody not 
just for the americans 
in cuscatancingo two young men said they fled the scene as 
soldiers ordered the others into the street 
one spoke to the associated press on condition of anonymity he 
expressed fear that soldiers would kill him if he accused them 
openly 
he and the others were sitting along a sidewalk nov 18 when an 
army patrol spotted them and ordered them into the main road the 
young man said 
most of them reached for identity cards and obeyed the order 
but the young man said he told his brother and a friend all out of 
sight at the end of the line that the three should run 
his brother said he had nothing to worry about and went with the 
group the young man said but he and the friend ran up a side 
street 
five minutes later they heard a volley of shots followed by 
single shots coups de grace and his brother and the others 
were dead he told the ap 
family members reported the killings to a justice of the peace 
who inspected the scene 
the judge who first dealt with the case said only a formal 
complaint from the young man could activate an investigation and 
i can only offer him security up to a certain point 
he also said coming forward probably would not make much 
difference 
we judges supposedly are the authority and the police 
supposedly are the auxiliary organs but the reality is very 
different he said on condition of anonymity 
i would have to depend on the police which are part of the 
armed forces to investigate the armed forces you see where that 
puts us 
proceso the weekly publication of central american university 
published an article in february on the cuscatancingo slayings 
three months after the two massacres those materially 
responsible for the murder of the jesuits have been arrested and 
charged it said the murderers of the seven young men in 
cuscatancingo on the other hand remain unpunished 
the contrast between the two cases is a example of how little 
the countrys judicial system has been consolidated 
notwithstanding the trumpeted advances the government has 
proclaimed with regard to the jesuit case 
