<TEXT>
on a fall day in 1988 botanist rajani 
nadgauda burst into her bosss office and shouted the bamboo is 
flowering 
the scientist led her boss by the hand to the greenhouse where 
in a beaker a bamboo seedling had sprouted tiny pale flowers 
like all bamboo buds they werent very pretty limp almost dry 
and close to colorless the flowers exuded no fragrance but to 
mrs nadgauda and her boss plant physiologist anthony mascarenhas 
they were beautiful 
thus began a groundbreaking experiment on the high emperor of 
all the grasses for almost two years the bamboo team at 
indias national chemical laboratory used rigorous science the 
potionmaking of a brewmaster and a good dose of superstition to 
coax successive groups of bamboo to flower the results were 
published march 22 in the british magazine nature 
the implications of coaxing a bamboo to flower in a laboratory 
are immense bamboo is an important raw material for paper and in 
construction its shoots are a popular vegetable in asia and its 
leaves and branches are used as livestock feed 
but understanding of the plant has been hampered by its bizarre 
life cycle when first growing bamboo spears shoot skyward at up 
to 16 inches per hour soaring as tall as 130 feet the grass 
flowers once every 30 years and some stands take as long as 120 
years most botanists die or retire by the time one generation of 
the tall grass dies and another flowers 
but on that fall day two years ago a glimmer of hope appeared 
if mrs nadgauda and mascarenhas could repeat the flowering they 
might be able to unlock bamboos secret with seeds from the 
flowers they could also crossbreed bamboo another first 
success could aid the fight against deforestation ravaging much 
of asia it also could increase production of bamboo success might 
even help halt the extinction of chinas giant panda which relies 
on the capricious plant for food 
using highly nutritious ingredients mascarenhas team took 
bamboo seedlings and tried to spark flowering 
we invented a powerful brew said mascarenhas we used 
coconut milk but we also added some secret things we felt a little 
like witch doctors 
the scientists showered their plant cultures with care 
you have to give love to your cultures to make them grow 
mascarenhas said of course we are scientists but we also know 
that nature moves in strange ways 
mrs nadgauda had the best luck with the cultures the 
fieryeyed 39yearold is known in the laboratory as a woman who 
does not suffer fools or stubborn cultures gladly 
if i look at the cultures angrily they grow she said i 
treat them like my children if they obey me then i love them 
mrs nadgauda said she would often place beakers of bamboo 
seedlings on her desk and glare at them in the afternoon 
the morning after one such scolding mrs nadgauda came to work 
to find her cultures had sprouted flowers the experiment had 
succeeded within a few months the bamboo team succeeded twice 
more prompting two species of bamboo to flower 
in an editorial attached to the nature article david hanke a 
professor of botany at cambridge university said the experiment 
opens up endless possibilities for the high emperor of all the 
grasses 
mascarenhas and mrs nadgauda are more modest 
we still have much work to do said mascarenhas we are 
perfecting the brew 
bamboo comprises about 500 species scattered throughout the 
world but it is in asia where it reigns supreme cutting a verdant 
swath through indias monsoon country the valleys of chinas 
yunnan and sichuan provinces over the korean peninsula and into 
japan 
in hong kong and tokyo bamboo scaffolding encases most 
construction sites on chinas farms bamboo hay feeds water 
buffalo and pigs shoots of the young bamboo are stirfried in 
shanghai and pickled in bombay in cambodia thailand and vietnam 
bamboo trunks lift farmers houses from the floodprone plains in 
bangladesh where houses and humanity are constantly swept away by 
cyclones and floods bamboo is split and woven into mats that serve 
as walls and roofs of hastily erected new dwellings 
mascarenhas hopes the bamboo team will soon be able to 
perfect the flowering experiment and begin selling the technology 
to other labs of course we love the plants he said but we 
could also use the money 
</TEXT>
