<TEXT>
breastfeeding may not protect middleclass 
urban infants in developed countries from infectious disease as it 
does in the third world a new report says 
the study found no effect on rates of upper or lower respiratory 
illness an ear condition called otitis media or an inflammation 
of the stomach and intestines called gastroenteritis 
the study done in denmark involved 500 infants whose health 
and feeding practices were tracked over their first year with 
monthly questionnaires 
previous studies have shown that breast feeding protects infants 
from infectious disease in the third world but researchers have 
reached conflicting conclusions about infants in developed 
countries maybe because of how they did their studies researchers 
said in the april issue of the journal pediatrics 
the american academy of pediatrics generally endorses 
breastfeeding for fullterm infants saying it provides 
nutritional economic and psychological advantages as well as 
bolstering the infants diseasefighting immune system 
the authors of the new study said their results probably apply 
to middleclass populations in the united states but not to rural 
or poor urban populations 
the researchers were from the albert einstein college of 
medicinemontefiore medical center in new york the yale university 
school of medicine and the university of copenhagen in denmark 
