<TEXT>
gases being studied as replacements for 
ozonedestroying chlorofluorocarbons would contribute to global 
warming but less than chlorofluorocarbons do a study says 
chlorofluorocarbons called cfcs are used in a variety of 
products but researchers want to find replacements because cfcs 
destroy ozone in the upper atmosphere 
the ozone shields earth from solar rays that can cause skin 
cancer 
the new study notes that cfcs also promote global warming 
through the greenhouse effect because they can trap energy 
radiating from earth 
most replacement gases can also absorb that energy researchers 
said but their potential contribution to global warming is only 
about onetenth that of cfcs chiefly because they break down more 
quickly in the atmosphere researchers found 
the work is reported in the april 5 issue of the british journal 
nature by scientists at ei du pont de nemours amp co of 
wilmington del and atmospheric and environmental research inc 
of cambridge mass 
in an accompanying editorial keith shine of the university of 
reading in england said unrestrained emissions of the substitutes 
could lead to climatically significant concentrations during the 
next century so it would be important to prevent unnecessary 
releases he wrote 
