<TEXT>
genetically engineered food could become as 
common as corn by the end of this decade say researchers whose 
recent breakthrough in the field already has expanded the range of 
products under development 
tomatoes that taste better and last longer will be among the 
first genetically altered edibles submitted this year for federal 
food and drug administration approval according to the company 
that grows them 
if the fda gives the green light to tomatoes 
herbicideresistant corn likely will be among the cornucopia of 
products that follow because corn has just joined the genetic age 
two teams of researchers say they have produced genetically 
altered corn plants capable of passing on their newly acquired 
traits to the next generation a problem that had stymied 
scientists for years 
the technique promises to produce new strains of disease 
insect and herbicideresistant corn that researchers contend will 
be better for livestock and people and better for the environment 
people have talked for a long time of the potential benefits 
of genetic engineering of corn but until you could put a gene in 
all that was hypothetical said thomas b rice president of the 
seed division of dekalb genetics corp of dekalb ill 
now well find out rice said 
a team of dekalb researchers announced their success with corn 
genetics wednesday two days after a group of agriculture 
department and monsanto co scientists announced similar findings 
at the same conference in keystone colo 
both groups used a gene gun to shoot microscopic genecoated 
bullets into corn cells which were then grown into mature plants 
the adult plants were fertilized with pollen and produced a new 
generation of seedlings which were shown to have the same genetic 
traits that had been engineered into their parents 
genetic engineering of corn the largest and most valuable us 
farm crop has long eluded researchers despite their success with 
soybeans cotton tobacco and tomatoes said michael fromm a 
molecular biologist at an albany calif research center operated 
by the agriculture department and university of california at 
berkeley 
fromm who headed the usdamonsanto research team said the 
technique used successfully with those crops involved a bacteria 
that did not work well with corn and other grains 
researchers using the bacteria technique have developed products 
such as bettertasting longerlasting tomatoes and 
herbicideresistant cottonseed calgene inc a davis calif 
company plans to apply this year for fda approval of the tomato 
said dan wagster calgenes chief financial officer 
with the fdas permission calgene expects to market the 
tomatoes beginning in 1993 wagster said 
but the fda filing is likely to rekindle the debate over genetic 
engineering which critics fear will lead to the careless release 
of new life forms with potentially disastrous consequences 
wagster said that what we expect with the application to the 
fda is that the controversy gets resolved 
the company hopes to document that its new tomato now entering 
its third year of field trials is still a food that is still safe 
as well as an improved product 
he said calgenes genetically altered cottonseed is immune to an 
herbicide that is biodegradable and more concentrated than those 
currently in use but farmers cant use it because it kills cotton 
plants as well as weeds 
if the new cottonseed is approved he said cotton growers could 
switch to that herbicide saving them money and causing less damage 
to the environment 
</TEXT>
