opec will hold an emergency session of 
its ministerial monitoring committee on may 2 to examine how to 
stop the fall in crude oil prices the organizations current 
president sadek boussena announced thursday 
the full opec conference scheduled for may 25 in geneva could be 
postponed until june 26 a statement by boussena the algerian oil 
minister said 
the statement did not disclose where the meeting would be held 
but said all 13 member nations of the organization of petroleum 
exporting countries would be represented normally eight nations 
take part in the ministerial monitoring committee 
the announcement of such a meeting follows a series of 
consultations between boussena and opec partners about the drop in 
oil prices boussena said consultations would continue to try to 
identify practical temporary measures which could be put into 
place with little delay 
the current opec reference price for crude oil is 18 a barrel 
production rates are fixed at 22 million barrels per day 
