<TEXT>
dayton hudson corp today announced an 
agreement to buy the marshall field amp co department store chain 
for about 104 billion from bat industries plc a british 
conglomerate 
the purchase of the famous chicagobased retailer is expected to 
be completed within two months the deal will link two of the 
midwests most prominent retailers and will expand 
minneapolisbased dayton hudsons presence in chicago and several 
other regional cities 
the definitive agreement with batus inc bats us subsidiary 
must be approved by regulators 
dayton hudson said it planned to keep all 24 marshall fields 
stores in illinois ohio wisconsin and texas open for business 
this is a once in a lifetime opportunity to add another 
premier name to our department store division said kenneth a 
macke dayton hudsons chairman and chief executive officer 
macke said at a news conference in chicago that he anticipates 
no problems in financing the deal and added junk bonds would 
not play a role 
he said it was too early to say what part current fields 
chairman philip miller would play in the chains future but macke 
and stephen watson president of dayton hudson both praised the 
role miller has had in fields over the past five years 
for his part miller who with other managers had mounted a 
buyout offer of their own said he was disappointed his group had 
lost 
we thought we were looking like the front runner said 
miller its always a surprise when you lose 
marshall fields one of the countrys best known department 
store groups was put up for sale last year by bat as part of a 
restructuring to defend itself against a hostile takeover bid by 
sir james goldsmith 
bat a large conglomerate with interests ranging from tobacco to 
financial services and retailing also is selling its saks fifth 
avenue division 
dayton hudsons department store division operates 37 stores 
known as either daytons or hudsons in their respective markets in 
seven midwestern states 
our department store division is among the most profitable in 
its industry and has produced 11 percent compound annual profit 
growth for the past 5 years its consistent performance over the 
last several years supports this acquisition macke said in a 
prepared statement 
we are very excited about the synergy created by these 
powerful department store names marshall fields hudsons and 
daytons each one dominant in its markets he said 
the newly acquired marshall fields will report to marvin w 
goldstein chairman and chief executive officer of the department 
store division dayton hudson is in the process of building two 
replacement and three new department stores by 1992 the addition 
of the fields stores will bring the total number of stores in the 
division to 64 
goldstein said the company expects that there will be 
consolidation of some functions but that those decisions will be 
made in the coming weeks 
the acquisition will be financed with a combination of 
internally generated funds and a mix of debt instruments the 
retailer said dayton hudson does not plan an equity offering 
the corporation recently reported record revenue and earnings 
for the last fiscal year with revenue up 12 percent to 1364 
billion and income up 43 percent to 410 million 
in 1989 dayton hudsons department store divisions revenue was 
18 billion and its operating profit was 179 million the 
division has more than 22000 employees 
dayton hudson also owns the target chain one of the countrys 
biggest discounters with 408 stores in 32 states and mervyns a 
moderatepriced department store company with 221 stores in 15 
states 
