<TEXT>
nike inc is embroiled in a 
milliondollar dispute with the us customs service over how the 
company makes its air jordan shoes 
customs says the athletic shoe and apparel company must pay a 20 
percent duty when it imports its shoes from asia nike claims it 
owes only 6 percent 
at issue are what is known in the industry as foxinglike 
bands that connect many makes of athletic shoe uppers to their 
soles 
nike says air jordans dont have the bands the government says 
they do and that makes the 120 shoes competitive with domestic 
manufacturers styles with the bands 
in a 10page ruling sent wednesday to us sen bob packwood 
the customs service reaffirmed a preliminary finding last year that 
the imitationleather versions of air jordans have foxinglike 
bands 
nike says the extra duty has been adding 10 to 12 to a pair of 
air jordans retail price since mid1989 when the agency first 
ruled on the matter 
the company has had to pay 8 million to 9 million so far on 
the 32 million pairs that have been imported thus far 
what theyve done is charge all that excess money to the us 
consumer and its not protecting anything said carl davis 
nikes corporate lawyer in washington dc 
air jordans are assembled with a foot frame method that 
attaches soles to uppers differently he said 
the games not over yet he added the only decision we 
have made is that well continue to fight it 
davis said the next step would be an appeal to the us treasury 
department which oversees the customs service or to the us 
court of international trade 
</TEXT>
