<TEXT>
grain and soybean futures prices closed 
moderately higher thursday on the chicago board of trade boosted 
by a late flurry of buying linked in part to delays in the south 
american soybean harvest 
rainy weather and sweeping economic reforms have slowed the 
movement of soybeans and soybean meal from brazil the worlds 
secondlargest soybean producer analysts said 
some of thursdays strength in soybean meal futures reflected 
buying of contracts by users looking to lock in purchase prices in 
case the south american shipping delays continue said joel karlin 
an analyst with research department inc a chicagobased brokers 
advisory service 
the crop markets had opened mostly lower amid concerns that the 
soviet unions reprisals against lithuania could jeopardize us 
grain sales to moscow 
but those fears were overshadowed by the soybean rally and by 
ideas the soviet union is seeking to buy more us corn karlin 
said 
at the close wheat futures prices were cent to 3 cents 
higher with the contract for delivery in may at 369 a bushel 
corn was 2 cents to 3 cents higher with may at 277 a bushel 
oats were unchanged to cent higher with may at 157 a bushel 
soybeans were 3 cents to 6 cents higher with may at 600 a 
bushel 
