<DOCNO> AP900419-0233 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission made it 
easier thursday for big institutional investors to trade privately 
in unregistered stocks and bonds a move expected to help lower the 
cost of raising money for us companies 
the new rule helps cut costs partly by easing disclosure 
requirements for companies making socalled private placements 
it also is seen as making the market for such securities more 
liquid by clearly defining who may buy and sell them that 
eliminates an uncertainty that made them unattractive to large 
investors and forced many issuers to sell the securities at a 
discount 
the rule change also is an attempt to woo foreign corporations 
previously put off by onerous us disclosure requirements to 
raise capital here 
the sec requires companies offering stock to the public to 
register and make extensive disclosures about ownership financing 
and other issues to protect investors 
but the sec eased restrictions on trading of privately offered 
securities which arent required to register and arent bound by 
us disclosure regulations 
only large institutional investors like banks pension funds and 
insurance companies that already hold 100 million in securities 
can qualify for the new private placement restrictions with 
certain exceptions 
the sec which has one vacancy approved the measure 40 
the rule rule 144a set a high threshold for participating in 
the private placement market to screen out unsophisticated 
investors who are more in need of such disclosures provided by sec 
regulation of public offerings 
the sec also approved rule changes that would make the national 
association of securities dealers portal trading system the market 
place for such unregistered securities and would clarify 
regulations governing foreign transactions of unregistered 
securities 
these rules will have a profound and beneficial effect upon 
the ability of issuers to raise capital in the context of todays 
global marketplace and will enhance the competitiveness and 
efficiency of our domestic markets said sec chairman richard c 
breeden who has been pushing to make the us securities laws and 
markets more competitive with foreign markets 
the result should be a lower cost of capital in our markets 
breeden said at the beginning of the threehour meeting before a 
standing room only crowd of more than 200 
linda c quinn head of the secs corporation finance division 
said the rule change would make it easier to sell privately placed 
unregistered securities 
it says that if you have a security that hasnt been 
registered and you want to resell it without any conditions you 
can do it as long as you resell it to the right person and thats 
the 100 million institutional investor requirement she said 
currently the law is unclear as to when you can resell it 
exceptions to the 100 million requirement are banks and savings 
and loans which must have net worth of 25 million in addition to 
the 100 million securities holding and registered brokerdealers 
that either own and manage 10 million in securities or act as 
riskless principles for qualified institutional buyers 
the rule changes will not affect small investors unless they 
have money in a big pension fund or mutual fund that invests in 
privatelyoffered securities 
breeden said that according to some reports the market for 
privately placed securities has grown from 158 billion in 1980 to 
1704 billion last year 
we hope this rule will have a beneficial effect even on people 
who dont buy securities at all breeden told reporters after the 
meeting to the extent that we can reduce the cost of us 
companies raising capital thatll benefit the people who work for 
those companies benefit the us economy broadly by helping make 
us more competitive 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

