all 13 members of the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries will attend a may 2 special meeting of opecs 
pricemonitoring committee the cartels acting president sadek 
boussena said thursday 
he said the meeting was called to discuss the recent drop in 
crude oil prices to 16month lows a decline that market analysts 
have blamed on opec overproduction during a period of weak seasonal 
demand 
the opec members probably could firm up the oil market quickly 
by cutting their own production quotas but some analysts said the 
cartel is unlikely to do so they said opec is more likely to hold 
out the possibility of quota cuts while it waits for the seasonal 
increase in gasoline production to eliminate the crude oil surplus 
that increase has already begun analysts said citing tuesdays 
american petroleum institute inventory survey which showed only a 
slight rise in us crude oil stocks and a dramatic increase in 
us refinery activity 
the 33 percent rise in refinery runs indicated most refiners 
have completed their springtime turnarounds when they shut 
down to retool for more gasoline and less heating oil production 
by june 25 the rescheduled date of opecs midyear conference 
the current crude oil glut may have been reduced to the point where 
opec no longer needs to consider cutting quotas beutel said 
in the meantime he said opec members may continue to hint at 
quota cuts just to keep prices from falling 
tom bentz director of trading for united energy inc agreed 
its basically a ploy to stabilize the market a little longer 
until they can make it to june 
