<TEXT>
union carbide corp said thursday its net 
income fell 53 percent in the first quarter because of weaker 
chemical prices and extreme cold at the end of the year that shut 
down some southern facilities 
the chemicals and plastics company reported it earned 94 
million or 66 cents per share in the quarter ending march 31 
down from 201 million or 144 a share a year ago 
the company had sales of 217 billion down 3 percent from 
224 billion in the first quarter of 1989 
union carbide attributed the decline to weaker chemical volumes 
and prices as well as shutdowns and maintenance because of the 
extreme cold that struck the nation late last year and early 
january 
the cold affected union carbides chemical plants in texas city 
and seadrift texas and taft la said company spokesman david n 
kernis 
the company said the earnings do not include recently announced 
sales of chemical businesses by union carbides chemical and 
plastics subsidiary 
union carbide reported 128 billion in sales from its chemicals 
and plastics businesses down 15 percent from the first quarter of 
1989 sales from its industrial gases division were up 32 percent 
to 718 million 
sales from its carbon products unit fell 10 percent to 175 
million 
</TEXT>
