<TEXT>
fastfood giant mcdonalds corp on thursday 
reported a 12 percent increase in its firstquarter profit and 
announced plans to switch from ice cream drinks and desserts to 
lowfat dairy foods and fruit sorbet 
the company recently was criticized publicly by a nebraska 
millionaire who placed national newspaper ads saying mcdonalds 
foods are too fatty 
mcdonalds reported net income of 1581 million or 43 cents 
per share for the three months ending march 31 compared with 
1417 million or 38 cents per share for the same period a year 
ago 
first quarter revenue rose 11 percent to 15 billion from 14 
billion mcdonalds said in a statement from its headquarters in 
the chicago suburb of oak brook 
systemwide sales including sales at franchised outlets as well 
as companyowned stores climbed 9 percent to 43 billion from 
39 billion 
chairman michael quinlan said in a statement the companys 
business remained strong despite intense competition and a slower 
us economy 
responding personally for the first time to the recent attack on 
the fat content of mcdonalds foods quinlan said mcdonalds offers 
highquality and wholesome food which fits comfortably into a 
wellbalanced diet 
he said mcdonalds would make the switch to lowfat milk shakes 
lowfat frozen yogurt and orange sorbet ice by may 15 the chain 
already has added nofat nocholesterol apple bran muffins and 
cereals to its breakfast menu quinlan said 
the lowfat milk shakes contain significantly less fat than 
the current milk shakes but retain the same great taste quinlan 
said 
earlier this month nebraska millionaire phil sokolof bought 
fullpage ads in major us newspapers saying mcdonalds foods are 
too fatty he called on the restaurant chain to cut the fat content 
of its hamburger meat by 10 percent 
mcdonalds first responded that it was experimenting with using 
vegetable shortening instead of lard for frying its french fries 
and hash browns 
the company then went on the attack itself by sending letters to 
newspapers advising them that sokolofs ad was inaccurate and 
warning them not to print it again 
mcdonalds spokesman chuck ebeling said thursday mcdonalds had 
been planning the switch to lowfat dairy products since last fall 
he said the company chose to announce the change at this time to 
combat public perceptions that may have been created by sokolofs 
campaign 
ebeling said mcdonalds wanted to demonstrate the fact that 
first of all sokolof is all wet in implying theres too much fat 
in mcdonalds menu and in inferring we havent been doing 
everything possible to enhance our menu in every way thats 
feasible with respect to nutrition and good health 
our menu is balanced and nutritious as it stands ebeling 
said these things are just an enhancement to it 
mcdonalds also has taken steps recently to combat perceptions 
that its heavy use of plastic and polystyrene foam contributes 
greatly to pollution 
mcdonalds began a pilot program last year in 250 new england 
restaurants that promote recycling of polystyrene food containers 
and other plastics 
earlier this week mcdonalds announced plans to spend 25 
percent of its 400 millionayear construction budget on recycled 
materials the company also plans to use recycled paper for 
carryout bags at 500 of its outlets 
</TEXT>
