<TEXT>
harold simmons lawsuit challenging the 
legality of the proxy war he lost for control of lockheed corp is 
pure harassment and without merit lockheed chairman daniel 
tellep said thursday 
the company also reported that first quarter profits rose 11 
percent because of lower tax payments 
simmons federal suit filed wednesday asks either for a new 
election or that his nominees for lockheeds board be declared the 
winners it alleges lockheed illegally engineered extra proxy votes 
through an employee stock ownership plan and played a variety of 
dirty tricks to defeat simmons 
the results of the election were clear and decisive tellep 
replied in a statement from lockheeds headquarters in suburban 
calabasas 
we are extremely disappointed that simmons has chosen to 
ignore the independently certified results despite losing the 
election by over a 20 percent margin 
tellep suggested again that simmons was interested more in his 
own investment than the good of the company 
we view this action by simmons as nothing more than pure 
harassment tellep said simmons action confirms our view that 
he is interested only in advancing his own agenda at the expense of 
other lockheed shareholders 
lockheed and simmons also revealed thursday they each spent 
about twice as much as they originally estimated in fighting their 
fiveweek battle which culminated at the aerospace companys 
annual meeting march 29 the incumbent board was retained by about 
a 32 margin 
lockheed spokesman stephen chaudet said the company spent 15 
million to persuade shareholders to reelect the board of 
directors it originally estimated spending would total 8 million 
simmons the texas billionaire who owns about 19 percent of 
lockheeds stock spent more than 10 million compared with an 
initial 6 million estimate said his chief strategist j landis 
martin 
martin said simmons bought about a dozen ads in national 
newspapers and in smaller papers in areas where lockheed does 
business that was twice the number he had anticipated he said 
simmons also spent far more than expected on mailings to 
lockheed shareholders particularly participants in the employee 
stock ownership plan martin said 
chaudet also attributed lockheeds extra expenses mainly to the 
costs of newspaper advertisements and shareholder mailings 
separately lockheed said profits rose to 69 million or 109 
a share in the first three months of the year from 62 million or 
104 a share a year earlier sales rose 8 percent to 225 
billion from 209 billion an increase spread fairly evenly across 
the corporation tellep said 
program profits were unchanged at 114 million but lockheed 
spent 13 million less on income taxes than in the 1989 period 
helping to boost net profits 
martin simmons chief lieutenant and the head of nl 
industries through which simmons bought his stake in lockheed 
declined to comment on the results 
simmons contends that lockheed the nations sixth largest 
defense contractor has been mismanaged under telleps leadership 
his lawsuit contends the employee stock ownership plan which 
also owns about 19 percent of lockheeds stock is an illegal 
entrenchment device set up by the board to put a large block of 
stock in friendly hands 
if the plans votes and a few sofar challened proxies were 
thrown out simmons nominees would have won the election the suit 
contends 
it also says lockheed moved up the annual meeting date by six 
weeks to rob simmons of time to campaign failed to mention 
simmons nominees in its proxy material and denied simmons a 
chance to present his case to members of the employee stock 
ownership plan 
